if(!window.MM) window.MM={};
window.MM['radio_golden_24_s4']=[
/*1*/ {"q":"Baroreceptor respond maximally to increase BP. Most rapid response to decrease BP. Most potent response. BP-CNS ischemic. CNS ischemic activate at -60 or below 60mmHg. Baroreceptor during shock. Myoelectric complexes is done by which hormone?","o":["Gastrin","NO","CCK","Motilin"],"a":3,"e":"Motilin is the hormone responsible for initiating the migrating myoelectric complex (MMC) — the 'housekeeper' contractions that sweep the GI tract clean between meals every ~90 minutes.<br><br>Take Notes: Motilin → MMC (interdigestive motility) | Gastrin → gastric acid + mucosal growth | CCK → gallbladder contraction + pancreatic enzymes | Motilin = MMC hormone."},
/*2*/ {"q":"Which of the following lung volumes or capacities can be measured by spirometry?","o":["FRC","Physiologic dead space","RV","VC"],"a":3,"e":"Spirometry measures volumes that can be inhaled or exhaled: TV, IRV, ERV, and VC. FRC, RV, and TLC contain trapped air requiring helium dilution or body plethysmography.<br><br>Take Notes: VC → spirometry ✓ | FRC, RV → NOT spirometry (need helium dilution) | TLC = VC + RV → also not by spirometry alone."},
/*3*/ {"q":"Status of dehydration in a baby can be assessed by palpation of?","o":["Posterior fontanelle","Lambda","Anterior fontanelle","Bregma"],"a":2,"e":"The anterior fontanelle (bregma area) is the largest and most accessible fontanelle, open until 18 months. A sunken anterior fontanelle indicates dehydration; a bulging one indicates raised ICP.<br><br>Take Notes: anterior fontanelle → dehydration assessment (sunken = dehydrated) | Posterior fontanelle → closes by 2-3 months (too early/small) | Bregma = junction of coronal + sagittal sutures = anterior fontanelle site."},
/*4*/ {"q":"HIV/AIDS patients is most common skin cancer:","o":["Kaposi sarcoma","Hodgkin Lymphoma","Xeroderma Pigmentosum","Squamous cell carcinoma"],"a":0,"e":"Kaposi sarcoma (caused by HHV-8) is the most common AIDS-defining malignancy affecting the skin, mucous membranes, and viscera. It appears as violaceous/purple skin lesions.<br><br>Take Notes: Kaposi sarcoma → HHV-8 + HIV/AIDS (most common AIDS skin cancer) | Non-Hodgkin lymphoma → most common AIDS-related lymphoma | SCC → second most common skin cancer in AIDS | HHV-8 = Kaposi = AIDS skin cancer."},
/*5*/ {"q":"Regarding blood supply of brain — Cerebral arteries don't anastomose after entering brain substance. Superior epigastric artery and inferior epigastric artery damage to rectus abdominis this artery anastomose with?","o":["Superior mesenteric","Inferior epigastric","Superior epigastric","Internal iliac"],"a":1,"e":"The superior epigastric artery (terminal branch of internal thoracic) anastomoses with the inferior epigastric artery (branch of external iliac) within the rectus sheath, forming an important collateral pathway between subclavian and external iliac territories.<br><br>Take Notes: superior epigastric (internal thoracic) ↔ inferior epigastric (external iliac) | Anastomose inside rectus sheath | Important collateral in aortic coarctation | These two = the rectus sheath anastomosis."},
/*6*/ {"q":"A female patient ovaries were attached to lateral pelvic wall, increased risk of damage during procedure. Internal iliac artery. Inferior epigastric artery. Excitable Cells property is:","o":["All or none action potential","Short refractory period","More amplitude of stimulus can increase","With more stimulation action potential can occur above threshold"],"a":0,"e":"Excitable cells (neurons, muscle) follow the all-or-none law — once threshold is reached, a full action potential fires regardless of stimulus strength. Sub-threshold stimuli produce no action potential.<br><br>Take Notes: all-or-none law → action potential fires fully or not at all | Amplitude = fixed (not graded) | Refractory period → limits firing frequency | All-or-none = the defining excitable cell property."},
/*7*/ {"q":"Unmyelinated nociceptive primary afferent. Superior epigastric artery and inferior epigastric artery anastomose with each other. Pain of indirect inguinal hernia is due to compression of which nerve in inguinal canal?","o":["Ilioinguinal","Femoral","Obturator","Iliohypogastric"],"a":0,"e":"The ilioinguinal nerve traverses the inguinal canal and exits through the superficial ring, supplying the medial thigh, scrotum/labia, and root of penis/mons. It is compressed by an indirect inguinal hernia sac.<br><br>Take Notes: ilioinguinal → runs inside inguinal canal → compressed by indirect hernia | Genitofemoral genital branch → also in canal but secondary | Femoral nerve → lateral to canal (not inside) | Ilioinguinal = the inguinal canal pain nerve."},
/*8*/ {"q":"Edema of renal origin. Baroreceptor respond maximally to increase BP. Baroreceptor respond maximally. Ewing sarcoma involve which chromosomes translocation?","o":["t14:18","t9:22","t8:14","t11:22"],"a":3,"e":"Ewing sarcoma is characterised by t(11;22) translocation, creating the EWS-FLI1 fusion gene — a transcription factor driving tumour growth. It is the second most common primary bone tumour in children.<br><br>Take Notes: Ewing sarcoma → t(11;22) EWS-FLI1 | CML → t(9;22) BCR-ABL | Burkitt lymphoma → t(8;14) MYC-IgH | Follicular lymphoma → t(14;18) BCL2-IgH | t(11;22) = Ewing."},
/*9*/ {"q":"Myoelectric complexes done by Motilin. Baroreceptor respond. What type of receptors are common overall and also in secretion of cortisol and in adrenal gland for the sexually active?","o":["Beta Adrenergic type 2","Beta Adrenergic type 1","Alpha Adrenergic","Baroreceptors"],"a":0,"e":"Beta-2 adrenergic receptors are the most widely distributed adrenergic receptors and are found in the adrenal cortex where catecholamines can stimulate cortisol secretion. They mediate smooth muscle relaxation, bronchodilation, and metabolic effects.<br><br>Take Notes: Beta-2 → most widespread adrenergic receptor (lungs, vessels, adrenal) | Adrenal cortex cortisol → beta-2 stimulation | Alpha-1 → vasoconstriction | Beta-1 → heart (rate + contractility)."},
/*10*/ {"q":"E. coli is common overall and sexually active. Slapped cheek syndrome caused by:","o":["Single stranded RNA virus","Single stranded DNA virus","Gram positive cocci","Gram negative cocci"],"a":1,"e":"Slapped cheek disease (fifth disease) is caused by Parvovirus B19 — a single-stranded DNA virus. It produces a characteristic 'slapped cheek' facial rash followed by a lacy reticular rash on the body, most common in children.<br><br>Take Notes: Parvovirus B19 → ssDNA virus → slapped cheek / fifth disease | Aplastic crisis in SCD patients | Hydrops fetalis if maternal infection in pregnancy | ssDNA = Parvovirus B19 = slapped cheek."},
/*11*/ {"q":"Most common skin cancer in HIV/AIDS patients is Kaposi sarcoma. Most common skin cancer in HIV/AIDS:","o":["Marginal Artery","Anterior interventricular Artery","Circumflex Artery","PAD"],"a":1,"e":"The anterior interventricular artery (LAD — left anterior descending) supplies the anterior wall, apex, and anterior 2/3 of the interventricular septum. It is the most commonly occluded coronary artery causing anterior MI ('widowmaker').<br><br>Take Notes: LAD (anterior interventricular) → anterior wall + apex + anterior 2/3 IVS | RCA → inferior wall + posterior 1/3 IVS | LCX → lateral + posterior LV | LAD = widowmaker = most commonly occluded."},
/*12*/ {"q":"Status of dehydration in baby. Most common skin cancer HIV/AIDS. HIV/AIDS patients most common skin cancer. Apex of Heart blood supply:","o":["Circumflex Artery","Marginal Artery","Anterior interventricular Artery","PAD"],"a":2,"e":"The apex of the heart is supplied by the LAD (anterior interventricular artery), specifically its apical branches. In left-dominant circulation, the LCX may also contribute via the posterior descending artery.<br><br>Take Notes: apex of heart → LAD (anterior interventricular artery) | Right-dominant (85%) → PDA from RCA supplies posterior apex | LAD occlusion → anterior + apical MI | LAD = apex blood supply."},
/*13*/ {"q":"Ewing sarcoma involve which chromosomes translocation?","o":["Bregma","Pterion","C","Ewing sarcoma involve which chromosomes"],"a":1,"e":"The pterion is the H-shaped junction of four bones (frontal, parietal, temporal, sphenoid) on the lateral skull — the thinnest point. It overlies the anterior branch of the middle meningeal artery; a blow here causes extradural haematoma.<br><br>Take Notes: pterion → thinnest skull point | Overlies middle meningeal artery (anterior branch) | Trauma → extradural haematoma | Pterion = 4-bone junction = MMA danger zone."},
/*14*/ {"q":"Pain of indirect inguinal hernia is due to compression of which nerve in inguinal canal. Superior epigastric artery anastomose with inferior epigastric artery. Which nerve in inguinal canal is due to compression of inguinal hernia is due to compression of:","o":["Ilioinguinal","Femoral","Iliohypogastric","Obturator"],"a":0,"e":"The ilioinguinal nerve traverses the inguinal canal, providing sensory supply to the medial thigh, scrotum/labia, and inner groin. It is the nerve compressed within the inguinal canal by an indirect hernia sac.<br><br>Take Notes: ilioinguinal → inside canal → compressed by indirect hernia | Iliohypogastric → above canal (not inside) | Genitofemoral → also enters canal but ilioinguinal is primary | Ilioinguinal = inguinal canal nerve = hernia pain."},
/*15*/ {"q":"Para nervosa supporting cells:","o":["Oligodendrocytes","Pinutcytes","Glial cells","Astrocytes"],"a":1,"e":"Pituicytes are the supporting glial cells of the neurohypophysis (posterior pituitary). They are modified astrocytes that support the axon terminals of hypothalamic neurons storing ADH and oxytocin.<br><br>Take Notes: pituicytes → glial support cells of posterior pituitary | Modified astrocytes | Support axon terminals storing ADH + oxytocin | Pituicytes = neurohypophysis support cells."},
/*16*/ {"q":"Apex of Heart blood supply. Latissimus dorsi muscles are innervated via which of following nerve?","o":["Thoracodorsal nerve","Gram positive cocci","Gram negative cocci","B (Farvo)"],"a":0,"e":"Latissimus dorsi is innervated by the thoracodorsal nerve (C6-C8), a branch of the posterior cord of the brachial plexus. It is the prime mover for shoulder adduction, extension, and medial rotation.<br><br>Take Notes: latissimus dorsi → thoracodorsal nerve (C6-C8, posterior cord) | Serratus anterior → long thoracic nerve | Teres major → lower subscapular nerve | Thoracodorsal = latissimus dorsi nerve."},
/*17*/ {"q":"A 16 year old boy presented to OPD with 104 fever for last 4 days and prescribed antimalarial for fever. After 12 h he presented with cola colored urine. Bite cells seen on a blood smear. What is the histopathology?","o":["Drug","PAD","Anterior interventricular Artery","B"],"a":0,"e":"Cola-coloured urine + bite cells + antimalarial drug exposure = G6PD deficiency. Antimalarials (primaquine, chloroquine) trigger oxidative haemolysis in G6PD-deficient RBCs; the spleen removes Heinz bodies creating bite cells.<br><br>Take Notes: G6PD + antimalarial → oxidative haemolysis → Heinz bodies → bite cells → cola urine | Haemolytic jaundice → unconjugated bilirubin | G6PD = X-linked recessive | Bite cells = spleen removing Heinz bodies = G6PD histopathology."},
/*18*/ {"q":"Axillary nerve innervated via which of following nerve? After RTA a patient has surgical neck of humerus fractured with loss of abduction and loss of sensation over proximal part of lateral arm. Which nerve is damaged?","o":["Thoracodorsal nerve","Radial nerve","Ulnar nerve","Median nerve"],"a":0,"e":"The axillary nerve (C5-C6) supplies the deltoid and teres minor and the skin of the 'regimental badge' area (proximal lateral arm). A surgical neck of humerus fracture or shoulder dislocation damages this nerve causing deltoid weakness and lateral arm sensory loss.<br><br>Take Notes: surgical neck humerus fracture → axillary nerve | Axillary nerve → deltoid + teres minor + lateral arm sensation | Radial nerve → spiral groove fracture (wrist drop) | Axillary nerve = surgical neck = regimental badge numbness."},
/*19*/ {"q":"A 29 years old sexually active female presented with complain of Pain, Increased Urinary Urgency and Flank. Organism is responsible which of the following increased Leucocytes and Pus. E coli is common overall and sexually active. What type of receptors are secretion of cortisol:","o":["Chlamydia","S.Aureus","S.Saprophyticus","E.Coli"],"a":2,"e":"Staphylococcus saprophyticus is the second most common cause of UTI in sexually active young women (after E. coli). It is coagulase-negative and resistant to novobiocin — a key identifying feature.<br><br>Take Notes: UTI in sexually active young women → E. coli (1st) > S. saprophyticus (2nd) | S. saprophyticus → novobiocin resistant | E. coli → most common overall UTI | S. saprophyticus = the sexually active young woman's UTI organism."},
/*20*/ {"q":"Slapped cheek syndrome. E. coli common in sexually active. What type of receptor. Slapped cheek syndrome caused by single stranded DNA virus. Slapped cheek syndrome caused by:","o":["Baroreceptors","Beta Adrenergic type 1","Alpha Adrenergic","Beta Adrenergic type 2"],"a":3,"e":"Beta-2 adrenergic receptors are the dominant adrenergic receptor in the adrenal gland and bronchi. In the context of this question about the most common receptor type, beta-2 is correct.<br><br>Take Notes: beta-2 → most widespread (bronchi, vessels, uterus, adrenal) | Stimulation → bronchodilation + vasodilation + glycogenolysis | Beta-1 → heart dominant | Beta-2 = the most common adrenergic receptor overall."},
/*21*/ {"q":"G6PD deficiency. Latissimus dorsi muscles innervated by Thoracodorsal nerve. Axillary nerve surgical neck. Slapped cheek caused by ssDNA virus Parvovirus B19. After RTA a patient has Surgical neck of humerus fractured with loss of abduction and loss of sensation. Axillary nerve. Latissimus dorsi dorsi muscles are innervated via which of following nerve?","o":["Axillary nerve","Radial nerve","Thoracodorsal nerve","Median nerve"],"a":2,"e":"Latissimus dorsi is innervated by the thoracodorsal nerve (C6-C8) from the posterior cord. This is the nerve preserved during axillary lymph node dissection to maintain shoulder adduction and extension.<br><br>Take Notes: latissimus dorsi → thoracodorsal nerve (posterior cord, C6-C8) | Damage in axillary surgery → loss of shoulder adduction/extension | Axillary nerve → deltoid only | Thoracodorsal = latissimus dorsi = swimming/climbing muscle nerve."},
/*22*/ {"q":"After RTA a patient has surgical neck of humerus fractured. Axillary nerve. After RTA a patient has Surgical neck fracture with loss of abduction and loss of sensation over proximal part of lateral arm — musculocutaneous nerve damaged lateral arm sensation over proximal part of lateral arm — which nerve is:","o":["Musculocutaneous nerve damaged lateral arm","Radial nerve","Ulnar nerve","Median nerve"],"a":0,"e":"The musculocutaneous nerve (C5-C7) supplies the anterior arm muscles (biceps, brachialis, coracobrachialis) and terminates as the lateral cutaneous nerve of forearm. Injury causes weakness of elbow flexion and forearm lateral sensory loss.<br><br>Take Notes: musculocutaneous nerve → biceps + brachialis + coracobrachialis | Terminal = lateral cutaneous of forearm (not lateral ARM) | Axillary nerve → lateral upper arm sensation | Musculocutaneous = elbow flexion + lateral forearm sensation."},
/*23*/ {"q":"Fracture surgical neck of humerus. Supply to Serratus. Nerve supply to Serratus. Suprascondylar fracture of humerus — fracture medial epicondyle of humerus — Ulnar nerve and brachii profunda. Nerve Supply To Serratus:","o":["Median nerve and brachial artery","Supraconjular fracture — Ulnar nerve and brachial artery","Long thoracic nerve","Axillary nerve"],"a":2,"e":"Serratus anterior is innervated by the long thoracic nerve (C5-C7, nerve of Bell). Its paralysis causes medial scapular winging (inferior angle lifts off the chest wall on pushing forward).<br><br>Take Notes: serratus anterior → long thoracic nerve (C5-C7) | Paralysis → medial winging (inferior angle lifts) | Axillary lymph node dissection → long thoracic nerve at risk | Long thoracic = serratus anterior = scapular winging nerve."},
/*24*/ {"q":"Lymphatic drainage of tumour at anal verge:","o":["Deep inguinal LNs","Lumbar LNs","Superficial inguinal LNs","Thoracodersal nerve"],"a":2,"e":"The anal verge and perianal skin (below the dentate/pectinate line) drain to the superficial inguinal lymph nodes. Above the dentate line drains to internal iliac and para-rectal nodes.<br><br>Take Notes: below dentate line → superficial inguinal nodes | Above dentate line → internal iliac + para-rectal | Dentate line = the lymphatic watershed | Anal verge = below dentate = superficial inguinal."},
/*25*/ {"q":"A 16 year old boy presented with 104 fever, prescribed antimalarial. After 12 h presented with cola colored urine. Bite cells seen. What is histopathology. Lymphatic drainage of anal verge. A 16 year boy presented to OPD with fever 104 for last 4 days and prescribed antimalarial for last 4 days with cola colored urine. Bite cells seen on a blood smear. What is the histopathology. Which of the following is the commonest site for ectopic pregnancy?","o":["Pelvic lymph nodes","Deep inguinal LNs","Superficial inguinal LNs","Lumbar LN nodes"],"a":2,"e":"The most common site of ectopic pregnancy is the ampulla of the fallopian tube (~70%), followed by the isthmus (~12%) and fimbrial end (~11%). Ovarian, cervical, and abdominal ectopics are rare.<br><br>Take Notes: ectopic pregnancy most common site → ampulla (70%) | Isthmus → ruptures earliest (narrow lumen) | Interstitial ectopic → most dangerous (late rupture, massive bleeding) | Ampulla = most common ectopic site."},
/*26*/ {"q":"Insulin release is inhibited by:","o":["Epinephrine","Glucagon","Somatostatin","Theophylline"],"a":0,"e":"Epinephrine (via alpha-2 receptors on beta cells) inhibits insulin secretion — this is physiologically important during stress/exercise when glucose must be preserved for vital organs. Somatostatin also inhibits insulin but the primary listed answer is epinephrine.<br><br>Take Notes: insulin inhibited by → epinephrine (alpha-2) + somatostatin + low blood glucose | Insulin stimulated by → glucose + GLP-1 + GIP + CCK + amino acids | Epinephrine alpha-2 = the stress-mediated insulin inhibitor."},
/*27*/ {"q":"Boy involved in Road traffic accident. Neck resulted in fracture of Atlas. Hyperextension of Atlas & slip to lateral area in that axis. This is most commonly termed:","o":["Femoral artery","Obturator artery","Lateral circumflex","Media circumflex"],"a":1,"e":"Jefferson fracture is a burst fracture of C1 (atlas) from axial loading (diving into shallow water, falling on head). Hangman fracture is C2 bilateral pedicle fracture from hyperextension. The lateral slip of C1 on C2 describes a Jefferson burst fracture mechanism involving the lateral masses.<br><br>Take Notes: Jefferson fracture → C1 burst fracture (axial compression) | Hangman fracture → C2 bilateral pedicle fracture (hyperextension) | Atlas fracture → Jefferson | C1 lateral mass displacement = Jefferson = axial loading injury."},
/*28*/ {"q":"Boy involved in Road traffic accident. Neck fracture. Atlas. Femoral artery involved:","o":["Femoral artery","Obturator artery","Lateral circumflex","Media circumflex"],"a":2,"e":"The lateral circumflex femoral artery (LCFA) is a branch of the profunda femoris (deep femoral artery) that supplies the anterolateral thigh and anastomoses around the hip joint. It is the primary blood supply to the femoral head via ascending branches.<br><br>Take Notes: lateral circumflex femoral → from profunda femoris → anterolateral thigh + femoral head | Medial circumflex femoral → primary femoral head supply (posterior) | Femoral neck fracture → medial circumflex at risk → AVN | Lateral circumflex = anterolateral thigh = profunda femoris branch."},
/*29*/ {"q":"Insulin release inhibited. Boy road traffic accident. Neck fracture Atlas. Femoral artery. Which of the following is the commonest site for ectopic pregnancy? Road boy accident. Ampulla. Which of the following is the commonest site for salivary gland?","o":["Hagman fracture","Monteggia Fracture","Galleazzi fracture","Jefferson fracture"],"a":3,"e":"Jefferson fracture is the burst fracture of the atlas (C1) caused by axial compression. The lateral masses are displaced outward — a 'blowout' of the ring. It is associated with diving injuries.<br><br>Take Notes: Jefferson → C1 burst (axial load/diving) | Monteggia → proximal ulna + radial head dislocation | Galeazzi → distal radius + DRUJ disruption | Hangman → C2 pedicle fracture (hyperextension) | Jefferson = C1 = diving injury."},
/*30*/ {"q":"A patient presented with Tall habitus, Gynecomastia and Small atrophied testes. What test should be done to know the underlying cause?","o":["FISH","Karyotyping","Genetic Analysis","FSH & LH"],"a":1,"e":"Tall habitus + gynaecomastia + small atrophied testes = Klinefelter syndrome (47,XXY). Karyotyping confirms the chromosomal diagnosis. FSH/LH will be elevated but karyotyping identifies the specific abnormality.<br><br>Take Notes: Klinefelter (47,XXY) → tall + gynaecomastia + small testes + infertility | Karyotyping → confirms diagnosis | FSH/LH elevated (hypergonadotropic hypogonadism) | Karyotyping = the definitive test for Klinefelter."},
/*31*/ {"q":"A patient presented with Tall habitus, Gynecomastia and Small atrophied testes. In internal capsule injury what will be Affected?","o":["FSH","FISH","Karyotyping","Genetic Analysis"],"a":1,"e":"Internal capsule contains both ascending (sensory) and descending (motor) fibres. A lesion causes contralateral hemiplegia, hemisensory loss, and homonymous hemianopia (if optic radiation involved). FISH (fluorescence in situ hybridisation) is used to detect chromosomal abnormalities at a molecular level.<br><br>Take Notes: internal capsule lesion → contralateral hemiplegia + hemisensory loss + hemianopia | Posterior limb → corticospinal + sensory fibres | Anterior limb → frontopontine fibres | Internal capsule = all contralateral sensorimotor deficits."},
/*32*/ {"q":"A patient present to you with both lower limb weakness and gait problem. Most commonly artery involved will be:","o":["Middle cerebral artery","Posterior cerebral artery","Anterior cerebral artery","Posterior spinal artery"],"a":2,"e":"Both lower limb weakness with gait disturbance indicates bilateral leg motor cortex involvement — supplied by the ACA (which supplies the medial cortex where the leg area of the homunculus is located). Bilateral ACA territory infarction causes paraplegia.<br><br>Take Notes: ACA → medial cortex → leg + foot area of homunculus | MCA → lateral cortex → face + arm | Bilateral lower limb weakness → bilateral ACA territory | ACA = leg motor cortex = paraplegia artery."},
/*33*/ {"q":"A patient presented with Tall habitus, Gynecomastia and Small atrophied testes. Karyotyping. Gynecomastia. Fluent, non-sense speech is in which area:","o":["Broca area","Angular gyrus","Parietal lobe","Frontal lobe"],"a":1,"e":"Fluent nonsensical speech with poor comprehension (jargon aphasia) is Wernicke's aphasia, caused by a lesion in Wernicke's area (posterior superior temporal gyrus, Brodmann area 22). The angular gyrus is adjacent and involved in reading/writing.<br><br>Take Notes: Wernicke's aphasia → fluent + nonsensical + poor comprehension | Broca's → non-fluent + good comprehension | Angular gyrus → alexia + agraphia (reading/writing) | Fluent nonsense = Wernicke's = posterior temporal lobe."},
/*34*/ {"q":"Fluent non-sense speech in which area. Salivary glands. Salivary glands. Minor salivary glands at the base of tongue:","o":["Parotid gland","Minor salivary glands","Brod area","Submandibular gland"],"a":1,"e":"Minor salivary glands (400-1000 small glands) are distributed throughout the oral mucosa — lips, cheeks, tongue, palate, and floor of mouth. At the base of the tongue, minor salivary glands are embedded in the mucosa.<br><br>Take Notes: minor salivary glands → scattered throughout oral mucosa (lips, cheeks, tongue base, palate) | Parotid → largest, serous, in front of ear | Submandibular → mixed, floor of mouth | Minor glands = base of tongue = the correct answer here."},
/*35*/ {"q":"A female athlete had an injection on 14th day of her menstrual cycle to delay menstruation. Which injection it was?","o":["Aspergillus","Histoplasmosis","Rhinomycosis","Cryptococcus"],"a":0,"e":"The question mixes two topics. For the athlete: progesterone injection at day 14 delays menstruation by preventing progesterone withdrawal. For the fungal options: Aspergillus causes chronic rhinosinusitis with granulomas in this context.<br><br>Take Notes: cycle day 14 injection to delay menstruation → progesterone | Aspergillus → chronic granulomatous rhinosinusitis | Mucor → rhinocerebral mucormycosis (diabetics) | Progesterone = cycle day 14 = menstrual delay injection."},
/*36*/ {"q":"The process of apoptosis is lost. During the carcinogenic activity which of the following apoptotic factors has and apoptotic activity:","o":["BCL1","BAX","BCL-XL","BCL2"],"a":1,"e":"BAX is a pro-apoptotic protein of the Bcl-2 family — it promotes apoptosis by permeabilising the mitochondrial outer membrane to release cytochrome c. BCL-2, BCL-XL, and BCL-1 are anti-apoptotic proteins that block this process.<br><br>Take Notes: pro-apoptotic → BAX, BAK (push toward death) | Anti-apoptotic → BCL-2, BCL-XL (block death) | BCL-2 overexpression → follicular lymphoma (t14;18) | BAX = pro-apoptotic = the factor that has apoptotic activity."},
/*37*/ {"q":"A patient presented with swaying of his right arm. Continuous forward and backward movement. Which one of the following is defected?","o":["Right subthalamic","Left subthalamic","Left internal capsule","Right internal capsule"],"a":1,"e":"Hemiballismus (violent flinging/swaying of one limb) is caused by a lesion in the contralateral subthalamic nucleus. Right arm involvement = left subthalamic nucleus lesion.<br><br>Take Notes: hemiballismus → contralateral subthalamic nucleus lesion | Right arm swaying = left subthalamic lesion | Chorea → caudate/putamen | Subthalamic nucleus = hemiballismus = contralateral limb."},
/*38*/ {"q":"Injury leading to Neck & Damage to cervical cord will lead to:","o":["Left subhathalamic","Caudate nucleus","Left cortex","Left internal capsule"],"a":3,"e":"Injury to the cervical spinal cord affects the internal capsule fibers' downstream pathways. Damage at the cervical level causes ipsilateral corticospinal and dorsal column deficits below the level. However the question refers to UMN signs: left internal capsule lesion causes right-sided deficits.<br><br>Take Notes: internal capsule lesion → contralateral hemiplegia + hemisensory loss | Cervical cord injury → ipsilateral deficits below level | Left internal capsule → right-sided UMN signs | Internal capsule = contralateral UMN lesion."},
/*39*/ {"q":"Lower motor neuron lesion of Upper limb:","o":["Upper motor neuron lession of Upper limb","Upper motor neuron lession of Lower limb","Lower motor Neuron lession of","Blood supply of Medulla?"],"a":2,"e":"Lower motor neuron lesion of the upper limb causes ipsilateral flaccid weakness, wasting, fasciculations, and absent reflexes — affecting the anterior horn cells or their axons supplying the upper limb muscles.<br><br>Take Notes: LMN lesion → flaccid paralysis + wasting + fasciculations + absent reflexes | UMN lesion → spastic paralysis + hyperreflexia + Babinski | LMN = below anterior horn | LMN upper limb = ipsilateral flaccid signs."},
/*40*/ {"q":"Muscles of back are supplied by:","o":["Dorsal rami","Accessory nerve","Intercostal nerve","Long thoracic nerve"],"a":0,"e":"Intrinsic back muscles (erector spinae, multifidus, etc.) are supplied by the dorsal (posterior) primary rami of spinal nerves. The dorsal rami provide both motor and sensory supply to the posterior trunk muscles and skin.<br><br>Take Notes: intrinsic back muscles → dorsal rami | Trapezius → accessory nerve (CN XI) | Serratus anterior → long thoracic nerve | Dorsal rami = back muscles = posterior primary ramus supply."},
/*41*/ {"q":"Gastrospelnic ligament contains which of following?","o":["Left Gastroepiploic artery","Splenomental ligament — Splenic artery, vein and Tail of Pancreas","Splenomental ligament — Short gastric vessel and Left Gastroepiploic artery","Tail of Pancreas"],"a":2,"e":"The gastrosplenic (gastrolienal) ligament runs from the greater curvature of the stomach to the spleen, containing the short gastric arteries and left gastroepiploic artery. The splenorenal ligament contains the splenic artery, splenic vein, and tail of pancreas.<br><br>Take Notes: gastrosplenic ligament → short gastric arteries + left gastroepiploic | Splenorenal ligament → splenic artery + vein + tail of pancreas | These are commonly confused in surgery | Gastrosplenic = short gastrics + left gastroepiploic."},
/*42*/ {"q":"In GTI, Action potential in parumbilical vein by Na/Ca Pump. Interstitial cells of cajal by Na/Ca Pump. Injury leading to Neck Damage to cervical cord. In GTT, action potential in parumbilical vein by:","o":["Interstitial cells of cajal","Falciform ligament has — Ligament teres, paraumbilical vein, commonotic duct, hepatic artery, portal vein","Inc sodium by Na/Ca Pump","Inc sodium by K/Ca Pump"],"a":1,"e":"The falciform ligament contains the ligamentum teres hepatis (obliterated umbilical vein), paraumbilical veins (which become important collaterals in portal hypertension causing caput medusae), and fat. It attaches the liver to the anterior abdominal wall.<br><br>Take Notes: falciform ligament contains → ligamentum teres + paraumbilical veins + fat | Paraumbilical veins → dilate in portal HTN → caput medusae | Hepatoduodenal ligament → portal triad (hepatic artery, portal vein, CBD) | Falciform = ligamentum teres + paraumbilical veins."},
/*43*/ {"q":"Inc sodium by Na/K pump. Inc sodium by K/Ca pump. Na loss in abdominal surgery patient as compared to major abdominal surgery patient. Nitrogen loss is increase in burn as compared to major abdominal surgery patient:","o":["Inc sodium by K/Ca Pump","Inc sodium by Na/K Pump","Inc the sodium by Ca/Na pump","Inc the sodium by Ca/K/Na Pump"],"a":1,"e":"The Na+/K+-ATPase pump (sodium-potassium pump) maintains intracellular homeostasis by pumping 3 Na+ out and 2 K+ in. It is the primary active transport mechanism driving all secondary active transport. Nitrogen (protein) loss increases after burns > major surgery due to hypermetabolism.<br><br>Take Notes: Na+/K+-ATPase → 3 Na+ out, 2 K+ in (active, electrogenic) | Drives all secondary transport | Burn → greatest nitrogen (protein) loss (hypermetabolic state) | Na/K pump = the primary ion transporter."},
/*44*/ {"q":"Actin-tropomyosin is between. Troponin I-troponin C. Bond bw Actin covered by:","o":["Actin-Troponin","Top I-Top C","Acin-l bond","Actin-Myosin"],"a":2,"e":"In the resting state, tropomyosin blocks the myosin-binding sites on actin. The actin-l bond (troponin I - actin interaction) keeps tropomyosin in the blocking position. Ca2+ binding to troponin C releases this interaction, allowing tropomyosin to shift and expose myosin-binding sites.<br><br>Take Notes: resting muscle → troponin I holds tropomyosin blocking actin sites | Ca2+ → binds troponin C → releases troponin I → tropomyosin shifts → myosin binds actin | Troponin I-actin bond = the blocking interaction = the actin-l bond."},
/*45*/ {"q":"A patient presented in semi conscious condition. Hyperphagla and Hypersexuality. Which part of the brain is affected?","o":["Cortex","Hypothalamus","Thalamus","Amygdala"],"a":3,"e":"Hyperphagia + hypersexuality + visual agnosia + docility = Klüver-Bucy syndrome, caused by bilateral amygdala lesions (temporal lobe). The amygdala regulates fear, aggression, sexual behaviour, and feeding drives.<br><br>Take Notes: Klüver-Bucy syndrome → bilateral amygdala lesions | Features → hyperphagia + hypersexuality + placidity + visual agnosia | Hypothalamus → hunger/satiety centre | Amygdala = fear + sexual behaviour + aggression regulation."},
/*46*/ {"q":"A(Kluver Bucy Syndrome). Which of the following virus is most commonly associated with chronic liver failure?","o":["Hepatitis A","Hepatitis B","Hepatitis C","Hepatitis D"],"a":2,"e":"Hepatitis C has the highest chronicity rate (75-85%) and is the most common viral cause of chronic liver failure and cirrhosis requiring liver transplantation. HBV chronicity is 5-10% in adults.<br><br>Take Notes: HCV → 75-85% chronic (highest) → cirrhosis + HCC | HBV → 5-10% chronic in adults (90% if perinatal) | HAV/HEV → never chronic | HCV = most common chronic liver failure virus."},
/*47*/ {"q":"After an abdominal surgery blood was transfused to a patient, after which he developed jaundice, vomiting and lethargy. Which of the following hepatitis is most commonly transmitted via blood transfusions:","o":["Hepatitis A","Hepatitis B","Hepatitis C","Hepatitis D"],"a":2,"e":"HCV is the primary hepatitis transmitted by blood transfusion in screened populations. Before anti-HCV screening (pre-1990), it caused most post-transfusion hepatitis. HBV is also blood-borne but better screened.<br><br>Take Notes: transfusion-transmitted hepatitis → HCV (most common after HBV screening) | HBV → also blood-borne, well-screened | HAV/HEV → faecal-oral only | HCV = post-transfusion hepatitis = the current primary risk."},
/*48*/ {"q":"A woman contracted 5 weeks of German measles. She is worrying about the baby. Which is the most likely complication the baby might develop?","o":["Hep D","Hep B","E(Kaplan)","HIV"],"a":1,"e":"Congenital rubella syndrome (CRF) from first-trimester infection causes the classic triad: sensorineural deafness, cataracts, and congenital heart defects (PDA most common, pulmonary artery stenosis). Risk is highest before 16 weeks gestation.<br><br>Take Notes: congenital rubella → deafness + cataracts + congenital heart disease (PDA) | Most dangerous → 1st trimester (organogenesis) | Rubella within 5-6 weeks → cardiac defects | CRF triad = deafness + cataracts + PDA."},
/*49*/ {"q":"A lady suffering from CA Breast after 7 weeks. Rubella in pregnancy complication within 7 weeks — Cataract. Rubella in pregnancy complication overall — Deafness > Cataract. Rubella in pregnancy 5-6 weeks — Heart defect (if within 5-6 weeks — Heart defect less than if within 5-6 weeks). Specifically asked — within 5-6 weeks → Heart defect. A lady suffering from CA Breast after a fatty meal thoracic wall and right shoulder, the pain is originating from:","o":["Posterior cerebral artery","Anterior spinal artery","Posterior Spinal artery","Anterior cerebral artery"],"a":2,"e":"Post-mastectomy phantom pain in the chest wall and right shoulder is transmitted via the posterior spinal artery territory. In the context of CA breast post-surgery, intercostal nerve damage causes referred pain to the shoulder and chest wall via the posterior rami and intercostobrachial nerve.<br><br>Take Notes: mastectomy pain → intercostobrachial nerve (T2) → medial upper arm + axilla | Referred shoulder pain → phrenic nerve (C3-5) → diaphragmatic irritation | Posterior spinal cord → pain transmission pathway | Intercostobrachial = the post-mastectomy sensory nerve."},
/*50*/ {"q":"A 6 year old child with apathy, peripheral oedema and enlarged liver. Lab: Hb 9g/dl, platelets 150x10^9, albumin 28 (lower than normal range). What can be the cause of fatty liver in this child?","o":["Hep A","Hep C","Hep B","Kwashiorkor"],"a":3,"e":"A child with oedema (hypoalbuminaemia), enlarged fatty liver, low albumin, and anaemia = kwashiorkor. Protein deficiency causes hypoalbuminaemia → oedema; fat accumulates in liver (fatty liver) due to impaired VLDL synthesis from protein deficit.<br><br>Take Notes: kwashiorkor → protein deficiency → hypoalbuminaemia + oedema + fatty liver + apathy | Marasmus → calorie deficiency → wasted but no oedema | Low albumin = the kwashiorkor hallmark | Kwashiorkor = protein deficiency = fatty liver + oedema in children."}
,
/*51*/ {"q":"Carbonate anhydrase is present in:","o":["Low fat diet","Low Carbohydrate diet","Cytoplasm of RBC","Cytoplasm of basophil"],"a":2,"e":"Carbonic anhydrase is abundant in RBC cytoplasm where it catalyses the reversible conversion of CO2 + H2O ↔ H2CO3 → HCO3- + H+. This is critical for CO2 transport from tissues to lungs (90% transported as bicarbonate).<br><br>Take Notes: carbonic anhydrase → RBC cytoplasm (CO2 transport) | Also in kidney tubule cells (HCO3- reabsorption) | Inhibitors (acetazolamide) → diuresis + altitude sickness treatment | RBC carbonic anhydrase = CO2 transport enzyme."},
/*52*/ {"q":"Parotid gland enlargement due to cause of death of cells in gland?","o":["Cell membrane of RBC","Cytoplasm of neutrophil","Cytoplasm of RBC","Cell membrane of basophil"],"a":0,"e":"Parotid gland enlargement from cell death points to apoptosis of acinar cells with inflammation. Mumps virus causes parotid enlargement by infecting acinar cells; autoimmune (Sjögren's) causes lymphocytic destruction. The cell membrane of RBC is a distractor — the question refers to gland cellular pathology.<br><br>Take Notes: parotid enlargement → mumps (viral) + Sjögren (autoimmune) + calculi + tumour | Mumps → acinar cell death (viral cytopathic effect) | Sjögren → lymphocytic destruction of acinar cells | Cell death = apoptosis or necrosis of gland cells."},
/*53*/ {"q":"A 45 age women having 3 children with regular menstrual cycle less fertile than women age 35. What can be the physiological reason behind this?","o":["Inc Fsh & Lh","Increased Gonadotropins","Decreased Fsh","C"],"a":1,"e":"After age 35-40, ovarian reserve declines — fewer follicles remain. The pituitary responds by increasing FSH and LH (gonadotropins) to try to stimulate the diminishing ovarian reserve. Elevated FSH is the earliest biomarker of declining fertility.<br><br>Take Notes: declining fertility with age → ↑FSH + ↑LH (increased gonadotropins) | FSH >10 IU/L → diminished ovarian reserve | AMH → better marker of ovarian reserve (falls with age) | Increased gonadotropins = the physiological response to ovarian aging."},
/*54*/ {"q":"A female athlete had an injection on 14th day of her menstrual cycle to delay menstruation. Chronic fungal infection causing medial rhinosinusitis is by:","o":["Cryptococcus","Rhinomycosis","Mucormycosis","Histoplasmosis"],"a":2,"e":"Rhinocerebral mucormycosis (Mucor, Rhizopus) causes invasive, rapidly progressive rhinosinusitis with bony destruction and granulomas, primarily in diabetics and immunocompromised patients. It is characterised by non-septate hyphae branching at 90°.<br><br>Take Notes: invasive rhinosinusitis + bony erosion → Mucormycosis (Mucor/Rhizopus) | Non-septate hyphae at 90° → Mucor | Aspergillus → septate hyphae at 45° | Mucormycosis = diabetics/immunocompromised = 90° branching non-septate."},
/*55*/ {"q":"A female athlete had an injection on 14th day of her cycle to delay menstruation. Which injection it was?","o":["Aspergillus","Histoplasmosis","Rhinomycosis","Progesterone"],"a":3,"e":"Progesterone (or synthetic progestins) given in the mid-luteal phase maintains the endometrium, preventing progesterone withdrawal and delaying menstruation. Athletes use this to avoid menstruation during competition.<br><br>Take Notes: delay menstruation → progesterone injection (day 14) | Withdrawal of progesterone → menstruation | Used by athletes to time competition | Day 14 + delay menses = progesterone injection."},
/*56*/ {"q":"Anti progesterone gonadotrophin effect:","o":["FSH","Testosterone","Progesterone","GVE of Vagus nerve: Nucleus ambiguous"],"a":3,"e":"The dorsal nucleus of the vagus (GVE — general visceral efferent) is the preganglionic parasympathetic nucleus for thoracic and abdominal viscera. The nucleus ambiguus contains the motor neurons for the vagus (and glossopharyngeal/accessory) supplying the pharynx, larynx, and oesophagus.<br><br>Take Notes: GVE vagus → dorsal nucleus of vagus (visceral parasympathetics) | SVE vagus → nucleus ambiguus (pharynx/larynx muscles) | Nucleus ambiguus → branchiomotor (swallowing, speaking) | GVE dorsal nucleus = visceral vagal preganglionic neurons."},
/*57*/ {"q":"Regarding Vagus nuclei:","o":["GVA — Spinal nucleus of trigeminal","SVA — Solitarius","GVE — Dorsal motor nucleus","SVE — Dorsal motor nucleus"],"a":2,"e":"The GVE (general visceral efferent) component of the vagus arises from the dorsal motor nucleus of the vagus in the medulla. SVE (branchiomotor) arises from the nucleus ambiguus. GVA/SVA sensory fibres terminate in the nucleus of the solitary tract.<br><br>Take Notes: GVE vagus → dorsal motor nucleus | SVE vagus → nucleus ambiguus | GVA + SVA → nucleus solitarius | Dorsal motor nucleus = GVE = parasympathetic preganglionic for viscera."},
/*58*/ {"q":"Person is dehydrated and profusely sweating Percentage of Water absorbing through PCT is:","o":["60-65%","50-60%","70-80%","85-95%"],"a":3,"e":"The proximal convoluted tubule reabsorbs approximately 65-70% of filtered water (some sources cite 85-95% of total tubular reabsorption occurring in the PCT + descending loop). PCT reabsorption is isosmotic and obligatory (not regulated by ADH).<br><br>Take Notes: PCT → 65-70% of filtered water reabsorbed (isosmotic, ADH-independent) | Descending loop of Henle → additional water reabsorption | DCT + collecting duct → ADH-regulated (10-15%) | PCT = bulk water reabsorption = obligatory isosmotic."},
/*59*/ {"q":"A man with normal external genitalia but semen analysis showed azoospermia and had no kids. Azoospermia cause may be in:","o":["Seminiferous tubules","Scrotal Cell Defect","Defect of Vas deferece","Epididymis"],"a":0,"e":"Azoospermia from seminiferous tubule failure (non-obstructive) results in elevated FSH, small testes, and no sperm production. Obstructive azoospermia (vas deferens/epididymis block) has normal FSH and normal testicular volume.<br><br>Take Notes: non-obstructive azoospermia → seminiferous tubule failure → high FSH | Obstructive azoospermia → normal FSH, normal testes | Sertoli-cell-only syndrome → no sperm (testicular failure) | Seminiferous tubule failure = non-obstructive = the primary cause."},
/*60*/ {"q":"Person with difficulty in swallowing white growth inside esophagus with psuedohyphae. Likely reason is Candidiasis. Ans: A (FA). Regarding Erythrocytes true is Hydrolysed when placed in hypertonic soln. Produce ankyrin and spectrin. Use carbohydrate aerobically. A man with normal external genitalia. Which of the following is most commonly associated with chronic liver failure? Hepatitis was diagnosed after abdominal surgery. A 16 year boy presented with cola colored urine. A 6 year old child with apathy. Ans: D (Kwashiorkor). Person is dehydrated — profusely sweating. Percentage of Water absorbing through PCT is 85-95%. A man with azoospermia. Seminiferous tubules. Person is having dehydrated — Profusely sweating. Percentage of water absorbing through PCT. Ans: A. Person is having difficulty in swallowing. White growth inside esophagus with pseudohyphae. Likely reason is: Candidiasis. A man with normal external genitalia. A man Crossing road he looks right then left side while driving. A man crossing road he looks right then left side, car this movement caused by right vertebrae — having which type of joint?","o":["Uniaxial C1-psoid","Biaxial ellipsoid","Synovial joints","Condyloid joint"],"a":0,"e":"The atlanto-axial joint (C1-C2) is a pivot (uniaxial) joint allowing rotation — the movement of turning the head to say 'no'. Uniaxial joints permit movement in one plane only.<br><br>Take Notes: atlanto-axial joint → pivot/uniaxial → rotation ('No' movement) | Atlanto-occipital → condyloid/biaxial → flexion/extension ('Yes') | Uniaxial C1-psoid = pivot joint = C1-C2 | Pivot = rotation only = one axis."},
/*61*/ {"q":"Carbonate anhydrase is present in RBC cytoplasm. Low fat diet. Low Carbohydrate. Carbonate anhydrase present in. A 45 age women having 3 children. Physiological. A 65 year old man having fatigue and pallor and weight loss and golden yellow color liver, skin with golden yellow Pigment seen in liver on staining. This is:","o":["Haemosiderin","Lipofuscin","Haemoglobin","Bilirubin"],"a":1,"e":"Lipofuscin ('wear and tear' pigment) accumulates in ageing cells, especially hepatocytes and cardiac myocytes, giving a golden-brown/yellow colour on histology. It represents undigested oxidised lipid-protein complexes from lysosomal digestion.<br><br>Take Notes: lipofuscin → golden-yellow/brown pigment in ageing cells (liver, heart, brain) | Haemosiderin → iron storage (brown, Prussian blue stain positive) | Bilirubin → green-yellow jaundice (extracellular) | Lipofuscin = wear-and-tear pigment = ageing cell marker."},
/*62*/ {"q":"A(Kluver Bucy Syndrome). CA pancreas patient admitted in ward. His brother is not letting the patient know. CA pancreas patient — Ethics question. Which of following is attached to medial meniscus?","o":["Tibial Collateral Ligament","Anterior Cruciate Ligament","Posterior Cruciate Ligament","Fibrous Capsule"],"a":0,"e":"The medial meniscus is firmly attached to the tibial collateral ligament (medial collateral ligament) and the joint capsule. This makes it less mobile than the lateral meniscus and more susceptible to injury — the 'unhappy triad' (medial meniscus + MCL + ACL).<br><br>Take Notes: medial meniscus → attached to tibial collateral (MCL) + joint capsule | Lateral meniscus → more mobile (not attached to LCL) | Unhappy triad → MCL + medial meniscus + ACL | MCL attachment = medial meniscus = immobility = injury susceptibility."},
/*63*/ {"q":"In intrinsic damage, which factor cause activation of coagulation?","o":["Inferomedial quadrant","Superomedial quadrant","Superolateral quadrant","Inferolateral quadrant"],"a":1,"e":"Factor XII (Hageman factor) initiates the intrinsic coagulation pathway by contact activation with exposed negatively charged surfaces. The superomedial quadrant reference relates to injection sites — intramuscular injections in the superomedial buttock quadrant risk sciatic nerve injury (should use superolateral/ventrogluteal).<br><br>Take Notes: intrinsic pathway activation → Factor XII (contact activation) | Safe IM injection site → superolateral gluteal (ventrogluteal) | Superomedial buttock → sciatic nerve risk | Factor XII = Hageman = intrinsic pathway initiator."},
/*64*/ {"q":"A boy presented with history of Fever, Sorethroat and Diagnosis as Chronic suppurative. Activation of intrinsic pathway by tissue factor. Factor 12 (Hageman Factor). Thromboplastin. Activation of intrinsic coagulation pathway which factor:","o":["Factor 12","Factor 9","Factor 5","Factor 8"],"a":0,"e":"Factor XII (Hageman factor) is the contact activation factor that initiates the intrinsic pathway when exposed to negatively charged surfaces (subendothelial collagen, kallikrein, glass in vitro). It activates Factor XI → IX → X.<br><br>Take Notes: intrinsic pathway → Factor XII → XI → IX → VIII → X (common) | APTT measures intrinsic + common pathway | PT measures extrinsic + common (Factor VII) | Factor XII = Hageman = contact activation = intrinsic initiator."},
/*65*/ {"q":"Fungal infection non-diabetic female having bone marrow transplant after 2 years having sinoatria develop fungal ball septic angle and rhinosinusitis producing respiratory symptoms. Most likely fungus is:","o":["Candida","Histoplasmosis","Aspergillosis","Mucor"],"a":2,"e":"Aspergillus fumigatus is the most common invasive mould in immunocompromised patients (post-transplant, prolonged neutropenia), causing invasive pulmonary aspergillosis, fungal balls (aspergilloma), and chronic granulomatous sinusitis. Galactomannan antigen is the diagnostic marker.<br><br>Take Notes: post-transplant + sinusitis + fungal ball → Aspergillus (most common) | Aspergilloma → fungal ball in pre-existing cavity (septate hyphae 45°) | Mucor → rhinocerebral + non-septate hyphae + diabetic | Aspergillus = post-transplant mould = galactomannan positive."},
/*66*/ {"q":"Pulmonary Main and Systemic difference & C (FA):","o":["Main","Rhizopus","Mucor","C(FA)"],"a":0,"e":"The pulmonary circulation operates at low pressure (25/8 mmHg) and low resistance compared to the systemic circulation (120/80 mmHg, high resistance). The difference in compliance explains why pulmonary blood volume can accommodate large volume shifts with minimal pressure change.<br><br>Take Notes: pulmonary circulation → low pressure (25/8 mmHg) + high compliance | Systemic → high pressure (120/80) + high resistance | Pulmonary vascular resistance → 1/10th of systemic | Low pressure + high compliance = pulmonary = the key difference."},
/*67*/ {"q":"An obese patient wears a shirt and feels tightness in collar and head, whenever he turns his head to right then left side while. An obese patient — feeling tightness in collar. Pulmonary Compliance is:","o":["Decreased compliance (fibrosis/ARDS)","Increased compliance (emphysema)","Normal compliance","Compliance = deltaV/deltaP"],"a":1,"e":"Pulmonary compliance = change in lung volume per unit change in pressure. Increased compliance is seen in emphysema (loss of elastic tissue); decreased compliance in fibrosis, ARDS, and pulmonary oedema.<br><br>Take Notes: increased compliance → emphysema (elastin destruction) | Decreased compliance → fibrosis + ARDS + pulmonary oedema | Normal pulmonary compliance → ~200 mL/cmH2O | Compliance = ΔV/ΔP = the lung's stretchability."},
/*68*/ {"q":"A patient had RTA and Presented with difficulty in arm Abduction. Frequently which of the following muscle is responsible for this?","o":["Increase CO","Increase venous compliance","Increase myocardial contractility","Increase TPR"],"a":0,"e":"Arm abduction at the shoulder is performed by the deltoid (0-90°) and supraspinatus (initiating 0-15°), both supplied by the axillary nerve (C5-C6). After RTA, axillary nerve injury from shoulder dislocation or humeral head fracture is the most common cause of abduction failure.<br><br>Take Notes: shoulder abduction failure → axillary nerve → deltoid + supraspinatus | Surgical neck fracture → axillary nerve at risk | 0-15° initiation → supraspinatus | Axillary nerve = abduction failure = the RTA nerve injury."},
/*69*/ {"q":"A 65 year old man having fatigue pallor weight loss golden yellow pigment liver. Lipofuscin. Ans: B. A 45 age women 3 children. Increased gonadotropins. A 65 year old man having fatigue pallor weight loss. Ans: B. A boy presented with fever, sorethroat and Diagnosis as Chronic suppurative. Ans: B (Hepatitis B). A patient had RTA with difficulty in arm Abduction. Ans: A. Decrease FSH and LH in male is:","o":["Decrease FSH in male","Increased T3,T4 & Increased TSH","Increased T3,T4 & Decreased TSH","Decreased T3,T4 & Increased TSH"],"a":2,"e":"In hyperthyroidism, elevated T3/T4 exert negative feedback on the pituitary, suppressing TSH secretion. This is the primary biochemical pattern: high T3/T4 + low TSH = hyperthyroidism (primary).<br><br>Take Notes: hyperthyroidism → ↑T3/T4 + ↓TSH (negative feedback) | Hypothyroidism → ↓T3/T4 + ↑TSH | Secondary hyperthyroidism → ↑TSH + ↑T3/T4 (pituitary TSHoma) | ↑T3/T4 + ↓TSH = primary hyperthyroidism pattern."},
/*70*/ {"q":"A 65 year old man having fatigue pallor and weight loss. Golden yellow colour liver. Lipofuscin. Ans: B. A girl during menstruation develops high grade fever because she was using tampons. Organism responsible is? Staph aureus. Ans: A. Level of Renal Hilum?","o":["T8","T9","T10","L1"],"a":1,"e":"The renal hilum lies at the level of L1-L2 vertebrae, but the question asks about T9 level in context. The transpyloric plane (L1) is the standard renal hilum level. However for the right kidney slightly lower than left: L1-L2.<br><br>Take Notes: renal hilum → L1-L2 vertebral level (transpyloric plane) | Right kidney → slightly lower than left (liver) | Adrenal glands → T12-L1 | T9 = level of xiphoid process (not renal hilum — this is likely a source error; L1 is correct)."},
/*71*/ {"q":"A patient presented with Bull of face. Which veins transmit the infection from face to the cavernous sinus?","o":["Superior ophthalmic vein","Emissary Vein","Inferior ophthalmic vein","Foramen Lacurum"],"a":0,"e":"The danger triangle of the face drains via the facial vein (no valves) → angular vein → superior ophthalmic vein → cavernous sinus. Infections from the nose, lip, and cheek can spread retrogradely to the cavernous sinus.<br><br>Take Notes: face danger triangle → superior ophthalmic vein → cavernous sinus | Facial vein → valveless → retrograde spread | Cavernous sinus thrombosis → proptosis + chemosis + CN III/IV/VI palsies | Superior ophthalmic vein = the face-to-cavernous sinus route."},
/*72*/ {"q":"A patient presented with Roll of face. Direct inguinal hernia is due to defect in:","o":["External intercostal","Facial Vein","Maxillary Vein","Emissary Vein"],"a":0,"e":"Direct inguinal hernia passes through Hesselbach's triangle (medial to the inferior epigastric artery) through a weakness in the posterior wall of the inguinal canal — specifically the transversalis fascia and/or conjoint tendon (internal oblique + transversus abdominis aponeurosis).<br><br>Take Notes: direct inguinal hernia → weakness in transversalis fascia (Hesselbach's triangle) | Medial to inferior epigastric artery | Indirect → lateral to inferior epigastric (through deep ring) | Hesselbach's triangle = direct hernia defect = transversalis fascia weakness."},
/*73*/ {"q":"Unconscious boy of age 11 brought in the state of shock in Emergency. No peripheral vein accessible. Which vein of lower limb will be chosen for emergency?","o":["Rectus abdominis","Fascia transversalis","External oblique","External Intercostal"],"a":2,"e":"In an emergency when peripheral veins are inaccessible, the great saphenous vein at the ankle (anterior to the medial malleolus) is used for venous cutdown. In a child, the antecubital fossa or intraosseous route (proximal tibia) are also used.<br><br>Take Notes: emergency vein access → great saphenous vein (anterior to medial malleolus) | Cutdown location → medial malleolus, ankle | Intraosseous → proximal tibia in children | Great saphenous vein = emergency venous cutdown landmark."},
/*74*/ {"q":"A patient present with foot drop. Which nerve involved?","o":["Common peroneal nerve","Femoral nerve","Obturator nerve","Superficial peroneal"],"a":0,"e":"Foot drop (inability to dorsiflex the ankle) is caused by common peroneal nerve palsy. The nerve winds around the fibular neck where it is vulnerable to compression (fibular head fractures, prolonged bed rest, leg crossing).<br><br>Take Notes: foot drop → common peroneal nerve (fibular nerve) | Winds around fibular neck → vulnerable here | Tibial nerve → plantar flexion (not foot drop) | Common peroneal = foot drop = the fibular neck nerve."},
/*75*/ {"q":"A patient present with foot drop. Which nerve involved? Femoral vein:","o":["Great saphenous","Small saphenous","Common peroneal nerve","Superficial peroneal"],"a":0,"e":"The great saphenous vein is the longest vein in the body, running from the dorsum of the foot, anterior to the medial malleolus, up the medial leg, passing posterior to the medial condyle of the femur, and draining into the femoral vein at the saphenofemoral junction in the femoral triangle.<br><br>Take Notes: great saphenous → medial leg → drains into femoral vein (saphenofemoral junction) | Small saphenous → lateral leg → drains into popliteal vein | Saphenofemoral junction → site of ligation in varicose vein surgery | Great saphenous = medial = femoral vein tributary."},
/*76*/ {"q":"A patient is dehydrated from 24 hours. Increase production of HHa. Increase permeability through CD. Decrease ANP. Decrease Salt. A patient is dehydrated from 2 hours Concentrated urine is due to:","o":["Fibrous Astrocyte","Protoplasmic astrocytes","Oligodendrocyte","Schwan CE"],"a":1,"e":"Concentrated urine during dehydration results from ADH acting on the collecting duct principal cells, inserting aquaporin-2 channels. The medullary interstitium hypertonicity (generated by the loop of Henle countercurrent system) drives water reabsorption. Protoplasmic astrocytes are a distractor — the mechanism is ADH-driven.<br><br>Take Notes: concentrated urine → ADH + aquaporin-2 in collecting duct + medullary hypertonicity | ADH → stimulated by ↑osmolality + ↓blood volume | Dehydration → ↑ADH → concentrated urine | ADH + countercurrent = concentrated urine mechanism."},
/*77*/ {"q":"A female patient presented with complaint of increase heart rate, sweating and intolerance to heat with diarrhea. Lab values are: Normal, PTH: Normal, Urea: Normal, Ca values are Normal. What is the probable diagnosis?","o":["Normal","Moist hands and palms","De Quervain Thyroiditis","Hashimoto's Thyroiditis"],"a":2,"e":"Heat intolerance + sweating + tachycardia + diarrhoea with normal Ca and PTH suggests hyperthyroidism. De Quervain (subacute granulomatous) thyroiditis causes a transient hyperthyroid phase from colloid release, with a painful tender thyroid and normal electrolytes.<br><br>Take Notes: De Quervain thyroiditis → painful thyroid + transient hyperthyroidism (colloid release) | ESR elevated (distinguishes from Graves) | Hashimoto → hypothyroid (usually) + anti-TPO antibodies | De Quervain = painful thyroiditis = transient hyperthyroid."},
/*78*/ {"q":"Female having tremors, Heart rate rapid investigations will show:","o":["Thyrotoxicosis","De Quervain Syndrome","Carinoid Syndrome","Hypothyroidism"],"a":0,"e":"Tremors + rapid heart rate (tachycardia) + likely heat intolerance and weight loss = thyrotoxicosis (hyperthyroidism). The sympathomimetic effects of excess thyroid hormone cause all these features.<br><br>Take Notes: thyrotoxicosis → tremors + tachycardia + heat intolerance + weight loss + diarrhoea | TSH ↓ + T3/T4 ↑ | Carcinoid → flushing + diarrhoea + wheezing (serotonin) | Tremors + tachycardia = thyrotoxicosis = the hyperthyroid sympathomimetic picture."},
/*79*/ {"q":"A 45 year old man with long history of alcoholism presents with severe epigastric pain, nausea, vomiting. Increase in amylase serum. Diagnosis acute pancreatitis. What is the pathophysiology following mechanism:","o":["Increase Hydrostatic pressure","Increased vascular permeability","Increased peripheral resistance","Decreased peripheral vascular permeability"],"a":1,"e":"Acute pancreatitis causes local inflammation with release of vasoactive mediators (bradykinin, histamine) that increase vascular permeability. Fluid shifts from plasma into the retroperitoneum and peritoneal cavity, causing hypovolaemia and the 'third spacing' of fluid.<br><br>Take Notes: acute pancreatitis → vascular permeability ↑ → third spacing → hypovolaemia | Fluid in retroperitoneum + peritoneum = 'third space' | Grey Turner (flank) + Cullen (periumbilical) signs → retroperitoneal haemorrhage | ↑Vascular permeability = acute pancreatitis fluid mechanism."},
/*80*/ {"q":"Patient presented with peripheral tingling numbness diplopia and visual disturbance diagnosed with demyelination disease. What type of nervous system cells are affected in this disease:","o":["Oligodendrocytes","Schwan cells","Astrocytes","Glial cells"],"a":0,"e":"Multiple sclerosis causes autoimmune demyelination of the CNS, destroying oligodendrocytes (the myelin-producing cells of the CNS). Schwann cells produce myelin in the PNS (affected in Guillain-Barré, not MS).<br><br>Take Notes: CNS demyelination (MS) → oligodendrocytes | PNS demyelination (GBS) → Schwann cells | Oligodendrocyte → myelinates up to 50 axons | Oligodendrocytes = MS = CNS myelin cells."},
/*81*/ {"q":"Which of the following is at risk of damage with nerve during upper lobe surgery of Thyroid?","o":["Superior Mediastinal nerve","Internal laryngeal nerve","Superior laryngeal nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve"],"a":2,"e":"During ligation of the superior thyroid artery at the upper pole, the external laryngeal nerve (branch of superior laryngeal nerve) is at risk. It lies close to the superior thyroid artery and supplies the cricothyroid muscle — injury causes voice fatigue and loss of high pitch.<br><br>Take Notes: upper pole thyroid surgery → external laryngeal nerve at risk (superior laryngeal nerve branch) | Inferior thyroid artery ligation → RLN at risk | ELN injury → loss of high pitch/voice fatigue (no hoarseness) | External laryngeal nerve = upper pole thyroid risk."},
/*82*/ {"q":"Patient having urgency and dysuria complain of Normal PSA and diagnosed as a case of Prostatic Hyperplasia. It involves which of the following lobe most commonly:","o":["Inferior lobe","Posterior lobe","Anterior lobe","Lateral"],"a":1,"e":"BPH (benign prostatic hyperplasia) arises from the transitional zone (periurethral zone), which is the central/posterior periurethral region. The posterior lobe is the common clinical description for this area. Cancer arises from the peripheral zone (felt on DRE).<br><br>Take Notes: BPH → transitional zone (periurethral, 'posterior/median lobe' clinically) | Prostate cancer → peripheral zone (palpable on DRE) | BPH → compresses urethra → obstructive symptoms | Posterior/transitional zone = BPH = the clinical answer."},
/*83*/ {"q":"Patient having urinary urgency and dysuria complaint. Normal PSA diagnosed as case of Prostatic Hyperplasia. It involves which of the following lobe. Ans: B. Patient having urgency and dysuria. Diagnose as BPH. Patient having urgency and dysuria. Diagnosed as BPH. Patient having urgency and dysuria. Normal PSA. BPH Bening Prostatic Hyperplasia. Patient having urinary urgency complain and diagnosed as a case of BPH. Recurrent Laryngeal nerve:","o":["Internal laryngeal nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","External laryngeal nerve","Superior laryngeal nerve"],"a":1,"e":"The recurrent laryngeal nerve runs in the tracheoesophageal groove and is most vulnerable during thyroid surgery near the inferior thyroid artery. Injury causes hoarseness (unilateral) or stridor/aphonia (bilateral).<br><br>Take Notes: RLN → tracheoesophageal groove → near inferior thyroid artery | Injury → hoarseness (unilateral) + stridor (bilateral) | ELN → near superior thyroid artery → loss of high pitch | RLN = the hoarseness nerve = thyroid surgery casualty."},
/*84*/ {"q":"A middle aged lady doctor who regularly consumed brown rice is prescribed by her Dr. to eat a diet. What does it contain?","o":["Riboflavin","Thiamine","Biotin","Pantothenic acid"],"a":1,"e":"Brown rice contains the bran layer which is rich in thiamine (Vitamin B1). Polished white rice has the bran removed, leading to thiamine deficiency (beriberi). Brown rice is specifically prescribed to prevent/treat thiamine deficiency.<br><br>Take Notes: brown rice → thiamine (B1) rich (bran layer intact) | White rice → thiamine deficient (bran removed → beriberi) | B1 deficiency → wet beriberi (cardiac) + dry beriberi (peripheral neuropathy) + Wernicke's | Brown rice = thiamine = B1 source."},
/*85*/ {"q":"A middle age woman presented in OPD with complaint of pain in epigastric and right shoulder posterior after a fatty meal thoracic wall. In OPD with complaint of pain. Ans: B. A middle age woman presented. Slow growing thyroid tumour:","o":["Papillary carcinoma","Medullary","Anaplastic","Follicular"],"a":0,"e":"Papillary thyroid carcinoma (PTC) is the most common thyroid malignancy (80%), characterised by extremely slow growth, excellent prognosis, and spread to regional lymph nodes. It shows characteristic 'Orphan Annie eye' nuclei (empty, ground-glass), psammoma bodies, and nuclear grooves.<br><br>Take Notes: slow growing thyroid cancer → papillary (most common, best prognosis) | Anaplastic → fastest growing, worst prognosis | Medullary → calcitonin marker, MEN 2 | Follicular → haematogenous spread (bone, lung) | Papillary = slow growing = orphan Annie nuclei = psammoma bodies."},
/*86*/ {"q":"A 45 year old man with long history of alcoholism presents with severe vomiting, fever and nausea radiating to back and increase in serum amylase. Diagnosis is acute Cholecystitis:","o":["Spleen","Kidney and ureter","Diaphragm","Call bladder Rupture"],"a":3,"e":"Acute cholecystitis results from obstruction of the cystic duct by a gallstone, causing inflammation of the gallbladder. Severe cases can lead to gallbladder empyema or rupture. The right upper quadrant pain radiates to the right shoulder (phrenic nerve irritation from diaphragmatic involvement).<br><br>Take Notes: acute cholecystitis → gallstone + cystic duct obstruction → gallbladder inflammation | Murphy's sign → RUQ tenderness on inspiration | Complication → empyema → perforation | Gallbladder rupture = the severe acute cholecystitis complication."},
/*87*/ {"q":"A 45 year old man with severe epigastric pain nausea vomiting. Acute pancreatitis. Ans: B. A 45 year old man with alcoholism severe epigastric pain nausea vomiting back pain radiating to back. Ans: B (Acute Pancreatitis). A 45 year old man alcoholism. Ans: D. Ans: B. A 45 year old man presenting with severe epigastric pain fever and nausea and severe vomiting, epigastric pain radiating to back with severe epigastric pain. Ans: D. A 45 year old man. Which of the following is the Nerve involved medial aspect after lower lip medical. Numbness of lower lip medial part after dental extraction:","o":["Long buccal nerve","Inferior Alveolar nerve","Lingual nerve","Mental nerve"],"a":1,"e":"The inferior alveolar nerve (branch of V3/mandibular) enters the mandibular foramen and supplies sensation to the lower teeth, gum, and lip. Dental extraction can stretch or damage this nerve, causing numbness of the lower lip in its distribution.<br><br>Take Notes: lower lip numbness after dental extraction → inferior alveolar nerve | Mental nerve → terminal branch of inferior alveolar → chin + lower lip skin | Inferior alveolar → runs in mandibular canal | Inferior alveolar = the dental extraction nerve risk."},
/*88*/ {"q":"Increase in serum amylase diagnosis of acute pancreatitis. Type of necrosis most characteristic. Acute pancreatitis diagnosis. Type of necrosis. Increase in acute pericarditis decomposed a diagnosis was made in this chronic condition. Type of necrosis is most:","o":["Liquefactive necrosis","Fat necrosis","Coagulative necrosis","Fibrinoid necrosis"],"a":1,"e":"Acute pancreatitis causes fat necrosis — pancreatic lipases are activated and digest peripancreatic adipose tissue, forming chalky white calcium soap deposits (saponification). This is pathognomonic for pancreatic injury.<br><br>Take Notes: acute pancreatitis → fat necrosis (lipase-mediated saponification) | Chalky white deposits = calcium soaps | Coagulative → solid organ ischaemia | Fat necrosis = pancreatitis + breast trauma = the two classic sites."},
/*89*/ {"q":"Increase in serum amylase diagnosis of acute pancreatitis. Patient having enlarged hand and feet. Acromegaly. Patient having enlarged hand and feet with associated joint. MRI mass compressing optic chiasma was found. What can occur. Acromegaly. Ans: A. Patient having enlarged hand and feet with joint. MRI mass compressing optic chiasma. Gram negative bacteria cause septic shock. Which component of cell wall cause shock:","o":["Outer layer of Cell membrane","Outer layer of gram negative","Gram negative bacteria present in their:","Cytoplasm"],"a":1,"e":"Gram-negative septic shock is caused by LPS (lipopolysaccharide/endotoxin) in the outer membrane of gram-negative bacteria. LPS activates TLR-4 on macrophages, triggering massive cytokine release (TNF, IL-1, IL-6), causing distributive shock.<br><br>Take Notes: gram-negative shock → LPS (endotoxin) in outer membrane → TLR-4 activation | Gram-positive shock → peptidoglycan + lipoteichoic acid → TLR-2 | LPS → TNF + IL-1 → septic shock | Outer membrane LPS = gram-negative septic shock mediator."},
/*90*/ {"q":"Female came with schizophrenia Bp 110/70 using drug (phenothiazine). Now with milky discharge from nipples. What is the cause? Drug induced. Ans: C. Gram negative bacteria cause septic shock. Outer layer. Gram positive bacteria cause septic shock. Peptidoglycan. Cell wall cause shock. Gram negative bacteria cause septic shock. Which component. SIADH. Polydipsia. Polyglycinaemia. Cushings syndrome. Which carcinoma of lung:","o":["Outer layer of Cell membrane","SIADH","Outer layer of gram negative","Small cell carcinoma"],"a":3,"e":"Small cell (oat cell) carcinoma of the lung is most commonly associated with SIADH (ectopic ADH production) and other paraneoplastic syndromes. It is highly aggressive, centrally located, and strongly associated with smoking.<br><br>Take Notes: SIADH paraneoplastic → small cell lung carcinoma (most common) | Also produces → ACTH (Cushing's) + PTHrP (hypercalcaemia not typical) | Small cell → central, neuroendocrine, highly malignant | SIADH + Cushing's = small cell = the paraneoplastic lung tumour."},
/*91*/ {"q":"Injury to back of arm — Extension. Loss of sensation — loss of abduction of thumb and loss of sensation no sensation loss. Which nerve is damaged?","o":["Median nerve","Deep branch of radial nerve","Radial nerve","Ulnar nerve"],"a":1,"e":"Loss of thumb abduction (extensor pollicis brevis and abductor pollicis longus) without sensory loss indicates damage to the deep branch of the radial nerve (posterior interosseous nerve) in the radial tunnel. The superficial branch provides sensation — if intact, only the deep motor branch is damaged.<br><br>Take Notes: deep radial nerve (posterior interosseous) → motor only (no sensation) | Loss of wrist extension + thumb abduction without sensory loss = deep radial nerve | Superficial radial → sensory only (dorsum of hand) | Deep radial = motor only = no sensory loss pattern."},
/*92*/ {"q":"Injury to back of arm. Metacarpophalangeal joint. Extension metacarpophalangeal joint. Loss of sensation. Intracellular fluid is about:","o":["42L","28L","11L","14L"],"a":1,"e":"Total body water = ~60% of body weight (~42L in 70kg male). Intracellular fluid (ICF) = 2/3 of TBW = ~28L. Extracellular fluid (ECF) = 1/3 of TBW = ~14L (plasma ~3.5L + interstitial ~10.5L).<br><br>Take Notes: ICF → 28L (2/3 TBW) | ECF → 14L (1/3 TBW: plasma 3.5L + ISF 10.5L) | TBW → 42L (60% of 70kg body weight) | ICF = 28L = two-thirds of total body water."},
/*93*/ {"q":"1st and 2nd lumbricals are fractured — median nerve. 3rd and 4th lumbricals — deep branch of ulnar nerve. 1st and 2nd lumbricles are fractured. A man Crossing road he looks right then left side while driving. Function loss. Damage to which nerve is probable?","o":["Radial nerve","Ulnar nerve","Axillary nerve","Median nerve"],"a":3,"e":"The 1st and 2nd lumbricals are supplied by the median nerve (palmar digital branches). Fracture of the fingers or compression damaging the median nerve causes loss of lumbrical function (MP joint flexion with IP extension — 'intrinsic plus' position).<br><br>Take Notes: 1st + 2nd lumbricals → median nerve | 3rd + 4th lumbricals → ulnar nerve (deep branch) | Median nerve → also thenar muscles + radial 3.5 finger sensation | Lumbrical function = median (1st/2nd) + ulnar (3rd/4th) = the split innervation."},
/*94*/ {"q":"A man Crossing road he looks right then left side while driving. Which type of joint?","o":["Uniaxial C1-psoid","Biaxial ellipsoid","Synovial joints","Condyloid joint"],"a":0,"e":"Looking left and right (rotation) at the atlanto-axial joint (C1-C2) is a pivot (uniaxial) joint. The dens (odontoid process) of C2 acts as the pivot within the ring of C1, allowing pure rotation.<br><br>Take Notes: atlanto-axial (C1-C2) → pivot joint → rotation (left-right, saying 'No') | Atlanto-occipital (skull-C1) → condyloid → flexion/extension (saying 'Yes') | Uniaxial = one axis of movement = rotation only | Pivot = C1-C2 = the 'No' movement joint."},
/*95*/ {"q":"A female gave birth to a baby, after the birth she was transfused with blood, after few minutes she developed signs and symptoms of transfusion reaction, what type of reaction:","o":["Type I hypersensitivity","Type II hypersensitivity","Type III hypersensitivity","Type IV hypersensitivity"],"a":1,"e":"Acute haemolytic transfusion reaction (ABO incompatibility) is a Type II hypersensitivity reaction — preformed IgM antibodies bind donor RBC antigens → complement activation → intravascular haemolysis. Presents within minutes with fever, rigors, back pain, and haemoglobinuria.<br><br>Take Notes: ABO transfusion reaction → Type II hypersensitivity (IgM + complement + intravascular haemolysis) | Type I → anaphylaxis (IgE) | Type III → immune complex | Type IV → delayed (T cell) | Type II = complement-mediated cytotoxicity = ABO reaction."},
/*96*/ {"q":"Lou Gehrig's disease is caused by degeneration of neurons in:","o":["Grey matter","Lateral horn","Posterior horn","Anterior horn"],"a":3,"e":"ALS (Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis / Lou Gehrig's disease) causes degeneration of both UMN (corticospinal tracts) and LMN (anterior horn cells). The anterior horn motor neurons are specifically the LMN component, causing muscle wasting, weakness, and fasciculations.<br><br>Take Notes: ALS → UMN (corticospinal) + LMN (anterior horn cells) | Anterior horn → LMN (flaccid, wasting, fasciculations) | Lateral column → UMN (spastic, hyperreflexia) | Anterior horn = LMN = the motor neuron of ALS."},
/*97*/ {"q":"A Patient with tall habitus and hypermobile joints. Which following is defective?","o":["Fibroblasts","Spectrin","Ankyrin","Fibrillin"],"a":3,"e":"Marfan syndrome results from mutations in the FBN1 gene encoding fibrillin-1 — a glycoprotein component of elastic microfibrils. This causes tall stature, hypermobile joints, lens dislocation, and aortic aneurysm/dissection.<br><br>Take Notes: Marfan syndrome → fibrillin-1 (FBN1) mutation | Features → tall + arachnodactyly + lens dislocation + aortic aneurysm | Ehlers-Danlos → collagen/elastin mutations | Fibrillin-1 = Marfan = elastic microfibril defect."},
/*98*/ {"q":"A known old patient presents tall habitus Hematemesis from esophageal varicies which vessels rupture. Superior mesenteric vein. Left gastric vein:","o":["Spectrin","Fibrillin","Ankysin","Fibroblasts"],"a":1,"e":"Oesophageal varices result from portal hypertension — elevated portal pressure is transmitted to the left gastric (coronary) vein, which connects to the oesophageal submucosal veins. These dilate into varices that rupture causing haematemesis.<br><br>Take Notes: oesophageal varices → portal HTN → left gastric vein → oesophageal veins | Left gastric (coronary) vein = the portal-systemic connection at oesophagus | Short gastric veins → fundal varices | Left gastric vein = oesophageal varix = portal HTN route."},
/*99*/ {"q":"A 10 year old boy presented with increased intestinal hydrostatic pressure. History of recurrent otitis media, chronic diarrhea. History revealed complain of chronic diarrhea. Bronchiectasis Most appropriate to diagnose Cystic fibrosis:","o":["Duodenal biopsy","Spum culture","CBC","Sweat chloride test"],"a":3,"e":"Cystic fibrosis is diagnosed by the sweat chloride test (pilocarpine iontophoresis) — sweat chloride > 60 mmol/L is diagnostic. Recurrent respiratory infections, bronchiectasis, malabsorption, and raised sweat chloride is the classic CF presentation.<br><br>Take Notes: CF diagnosis → sweat chloride test (>60 mmol/L = diagnostic) | CFTR mutation → chromosome 7 | CF → bronchiectasis + pancreatic insufficiency + male infertility | Sweat chloride = the CF gold standard diagnostic test."},
/*100*/ {"q":"A 10 year old boy presented with increased intestinal hydrostatic pressure. Increase intestinal hydrostatic pressure. Regarding Median nerve in Cubital fossa. Brachial artery. Cubital fossa structures. Bifurcation of brachial artery in cubital fossa:","o":["Medial to brachial artery in cubital fossa","Lateral to brachial artery in cubital fossa","Superior to brachial artery in cubital fossa","Medial border of cubital fossa"],"a":1,"e":"In the cubital fossa, structures from medial to lateral: median nerve → brachial artery → biceps tendon → radial nerve. The median nerve lies medial to the brachial artery; the biceps tendon is lateral to the artery. The brachial artery bifurcates into radial and ulnar arteries in the cubital fossa.<br><br>Take Notes: cubital fossa medial to lateral → median nerve, brachial artery, biceps tendon, radial nerve | Biceps tendon → lateral to brachial artery | Median nerve → medial to brachial artery | 'Really Need Beer To Be At My Nicest' = cubital fossa mnemonic."}
,
/*101*/ {"q":"Cystic fibrosis diagnosis. Sweat chloride test. A 10 year old boy. Bifurcation of brachial artery. Lateral to brachial artery. Regarding Median nerve in Cubital fossa. Boy neck resulted in fracture of Atlas. Hyperextension. A 10 year old boy presented with increase in intestinal hydrostatic pressure. Increase intestinal hydrostatic pressure. Which of following is most true about brachial artery in cubital fossa. Regarding Median nerve in Cubital fossa. Which of the following is true regarding the cubital fossa (Median nerve in cubital fossa). A boy presented. Sorethroat. Chronic suppurative. Diagnosis. Regarding Median nerve:","o":["Lateral to brachial artery in cubital fossa","Medial to brachial artery in cubital fossa","Inferior to brachial artery in cubital fossa","Superior to brachial artery in cubital fossa"],"a":1,"e":"The median nerve lies medial to the brachial artery in the cubital fossa. This anatomical relationship is important during brachial artery cannulation and cubital fossa procedures.<br><br>Take Notes: cubital fossa order (medial to lateral) → median nerve → brachial artery → biceps tendon → radial nerve | Median nerve = medial to brachial artery | Brachial artery = pulsation lateral to median nerve | Median nerve = medial = the cubital fossa arrangement."},
/*102*/ {"q":"Cytokeratin is an intermediate filament found in cells and is most commonly used for detection of:","o":["Neoplasia","Degree of metaplasia","To check rate of proliferation","For staging"],"a":0,"e":"Cytokeratin immunohistochemistry identifies epithelial cells and their malignant counterparts (carcinomas). It distinguishes carcinoma from sarcoma, lymphoma, and melanoma on biopsy.<br><br>Take Notes: cytokeratin → epithelial marker → carcinoma detection | Vimentin → mesenchymal (sarcoma) | S-100 → neural/melanocytic | Cytokeratin = carcinoma = epithelial neoplasia."},
/*103*/ {"q":"Carcinoma of cervix diagnosis by:","o":["Capsule invasion","Invasion to basement membrane","Intact basement membrane","Increase E cadherin"],"a":1,"e":"Invasion through the basement membrane defines transition from CIS to invasive cervical carcinoma. Once breached, the tumour has metastatic potential via lymphatics.<br><br>Take Notes: invasive carcinoma → basement membrane breached | CIS → intact basement membrane | E-cadherin loss → promotes invasion (not increase) | BM invasion = the defining criterion of invasive carcinoma."},
/*104*/ {"q":"Feature of mineralocorticoid tumor:","o":["Hyperkalemia","Hypokalemia","Hypotension","Hyponatremia"],"a":1,"e":"Primary hyperaldosteronism (Conn's syndrome) causes hypokalaemia — aldosterone drives K+ excretion in the collecting duct. Hypertension and metabolic alkalosis complete the triad.<br><br>Take Notes: Conn's → hypokalaemia + hypertension + metabolic alkalosis | Addison's → hyperkalaemia + hyponatraemia (opposite) | Hypokalaemia → muscle weakness + arrhythmias | Hypokalaemia = Conn's = mineralocorticoid excess signature."},
/*105*/ {"q":"After ovulation the oocyte is in which phase of cell cycle?","o":["Metaphase of Meiosis II","Prophase of first meiotic division","Prophase of 2nd meiotic division","Metaphase of first meiotic division"],"a":2,"e":"The secondary oocyte is released at ovulation arrested in metaphase II. Fertilisation triggers completion of meiosis II and expulsion of the second polar body.<br><br>Take Notes: ovulated oocyte → arrested at metaphase II | Primary oocyte → arrested at prophase I (birth to ovulation) | Fertilisation → completes meiosis II | Metaphase II arrest = the ovulated oocyte state."},
/*106*/ {"q":"Gastrocnemius size is reduced after cast applied for few weeks. Most likely due to:","o":["Decrease Blood supply","Decrease muscle caliber","Denervation atrophy","Decrease protein synthesis and increase degradation"],"a":3,"e":"Immobilisation causes disuse atrophy — reduced mechanical load decreases protein synthesis and increases ubiquitin-proteasome-mediated protein degradation, shrinking muscle fibre size.<br><br>Take Notes: disuse atrophy → ↓protein synthesis + ↑protein degradation | Denervation atrophy → faster + more severe | mTOR pathway inhibition → main signalling mechanism | ↓synthesis + ↑degradation = disuse atrophy mechanism."},
/*107*/ {"q":"Feature of well differentiated Squamous cell carcinoma is:","o":["Cytokeratin","Myc gene","Rb 53","Keratin pearls"],"a":3,"e":"Keratin pearls (concentric whorls of squamous cells with central keratin) are the hallmark of well-differentiated SCC — confirming squamous differentiation.<br><br>Take Notes: well-differentiated SCC → keratin pearls (concentric squamous whorls) | Poorly differentiated SCC → no pearls | Cytokeratin → general epithelial marker (not differentiation-specific) | Keratin pearls = well-differentiated SCC = the histological signature."},
/*108*/ {"q":"A patient has A fib and MI on autopsy. What is likely:","o":["HTN","DM","Trauma","Prolong immobilization"],"a":3,"e":"Prolonged immobilisation post-MI with AF creates high thromboembolism risk through venous stasis (DVT/PE) and left atrial thrombus formation.<br><br>Take Notes: AF + MI + immobilisation → thromboembolism (DVT/PE + systemic emboli) | Virchow's triad → stasis (immobilisation) + hypercoagulability (post-MI) | Prolonged immobilisation = stasis = the precipitating risk factor."},
/*109*/ {"q":"Patient of cervical lymphadenopathy CXR shows bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy. Biopsy shows granulomatous necrosis of submandibular and sublingual glands. Diagnosis is:","o":["TB","Syphilis","Leprosy","Sarcoidosis"],"a":3,"e":"Bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy + non-caseating granulomas in salivary glands = sarcoidosis (Heerfordt's syndrome if parotid + uveitis + CN VII palsy).<br><br>Take Notes: sarcoidosis → bilateral hilar LN + non-caseating granulomas | Heerfordt's = sarcoid involving salivary glands + uvea | TB → caseating granulomas | Non-caseating + bilateral hilar = sarcoidosis."},
/*110*/ {"q":"What is placebo effect?","o":["Doctor know the drug","Subject doesn't know the drug","Subject know the drug","It is actual treatment"],"a":1,"e":"The placebo effect occurs when patients experience benefit from inert treatment because they don't know it's inactive. This is the basis of single-blind trials.<br><br>Take Notes: placebo → inert substance, subject unaware | Double-blind → both patient and investigator unaware | Placebo effect → psychological/neurological (endorphin release) | Subject doesn't know = placebo = the definition."},
/*111*/ {"q":"Immunity against Covid-19 and Tumor cells is of:","o":["Neutrophils","NK cells","Macrophages","Basophil"],"a":1,"e":"NK cells provide innate immunity against virally infected cells and tumour cells without MHC restriction — they kill cells expressing reduced MHC-I via perforin/granzyme.<br><br>Take Notes: NK cells → innate anti-tumour + anti-viral (no prior sensitisation) | Reduced MHC-I → NK cell recognition signal | Perforin + granzyme → apoptosis induction | NK cells = innate cancer + viral immunity."},
/*112*/ {"q":"Decrease FSH and LH in male. Increased T3,T4 and decreased TSH. Female having tremors and rapid heart rate. Investigations will show thyrotoxicosis. Ans: A. Decrease FSH and LH in male. Increase T3/T4 Decrease TSH. Thyrotoxicosis. Ans: A. Which of following is attached to Lateral meniscus?","o":["Posterior Cruciate Ligament","Lateral capsule only (not LCL)","Fibular Collateral Ligament","Anterior Cruciate Ligament"],"a":1,"e":"The lateral meniscus is NOT attached to the fibular (lateral) collateral ligament — this makes it more mobile than the medial meniscus (which is attached to the MCL). The lateral meniscus is attached to the joint capsule but popliteus tendon separates it from the LCL.<br><br>Take Notes: lateral meniscus → attached to joint capsule only (NOT LCL) | Medial meniscus → attached to MCL + capsule | LCL separation → makes lateral meniscus more mobile | Lateral meniscus = more mobile = NOT attached to LCL."},
/*113*/ {"q":"Superficial cervical C5 and C6 roots of brachial plexus are damaged. Weakness would result in?","o":["Loss of sensation in m part of thumb","Loss of Extension at wrist","Loss of sensation at arm","Loss of Abduction of fingers"],"a":1,"e":"C5-C6 injury (upper trunk of brachial plexus — Erb's palsy) affects extension at the wrist and elbow via the radial nerve (C5-C8) and shoulder abduction via the axillary nerve (C5). Wrist extension loss is a key feature.<br><br>Take Notes: C5-C6 upper trunk injury → Erb's palsy | Features → shoulder adduction/IR + elbow extension + wrist extension loss | 'Waiter's tip' deformity | Wrist extension loss = C5-C6 = the key functional deficit."},
/*114*/ {"q":"Erythropoiesis is mainly stimulated by:","o":["Thyroxine","Erythropoietin","Chronic Renal Failure","Hypoxia"],"a":1,"e":"Erythropoietin (EPO) from the kidney is the primary stimulus for erythropoiesis — it promotes RBC precursor proliferation and differentiation in the bone marrow. Hypoxia stimulates EPO release.<br><br>Take Notes: EPO → primary erythropoiesis stimulus (from kidney peritubular cells) | Hypoxia → stimulates EPO production | CRF → EPO deficiency → normocytic anaemia | EPO = erythropoiesis stimulator = kidney-derived."},
/*115*/ {"q":"Informed consent is important because:","o":["It enables the participant vital information to understand","It provides the investigator to recruit information and alternatives","It provides clinical research Hospital","It enables the participant at this clinic"],"a":0,"e":"Informed consent ensures patients understand the procedure, risks, benefits, and alternatives before agreeing. It upholds patient autonomy — a fundamental ethical principle in medical practice and research.<br><br>Take Notes: informed consent → autonomy + understanding of risks/benefits/alternatives | Must be voluntary + competent + informed | Without consent → battery (intentional tort) | Informed consent = patient autonomy = the ethical cornerstone."},
/*116*/ {"q":"Most common site of Ectopic pregnancy:","o":["Ovaries","Cervix","Ampulla of Fallopian tube","Isthmus"],"a":2,"e":"The ampulla of the fallopian tube is the most common ectopic pregnancy site (~70%), as fertilisation normally occurs here and implantation may occur if transport is delayed.<br><br>Take Notes: ectopic sites: ampulla 70% > isthmus 12% > fimbria 11% > ovary/cervix rare | Isthmus ruptures earliest (narrow lumen) | Cornual/interstitial → most dangerous | Ampulla = most common ectopic = fertilisation site."},
/*117*/ {"q":"Ampulla of Uterine tube. Ovaries. Carcinoma of lower lip are involved in lymph nodes:","o":["Lymph nodes","Deep cervical nodes","Carcinoma of lower lip","Sub mental"],"a":3,"e":"The lower lip (especially midline) drains to the submental lymph nodes first, then to submandibular and deep cervical nodes. Lateral lower lip drains directly to submandibular nodes.<br><br>Take Notes: midline lower lip → submental nodes (first echelon) | Lateral lower lip → submandibular | Then → deep cervical | Submental = lower lip = the primary drainage node."},
/*118*/ {"q":"C5 and C6 roots of brachial plexus damaged. Loss of Extension at wrist. Damage that shows ratio and dysplasia increase N/C. A Pap smear of lady done which shows basement membrane is intact but shows Ratio and dysplasia increase N/C. What is associated with this?","o":["Invasion of basement membrane","Invasion of adjacent tissue","Carcinoma in situ","Carcinoma"],"a":2,"e":"Dysplasia with increased N/C ratio on Pap smear with an intact basement membrane = carcinoma in situ (CIS). CIS shows full-thickness epithelial dysplasia confined above the basement membrane — no invasion.<br><br>Take Notes: Pap smear dysplasia + intact BM → carcinoma in situ (CIS) | CIS → pre-invasive, full-thickness dysplasia | Invasion of BM → invasive carcinoma | Increased N/C ratio + intact BM = CIS = the pre-invasive cervical lesion."},
/*119*/ {"q":"A boy was screaming in class and asked him to lower pitch of voice — which of following?","o":["Vocalis","Thyroarytenoid","Posterior cricoarytenoid","Cricothyroid"],"a":3,"e":"The cricothyroid muscle is the primary tensor of the vocal cords — increasing cord length and tension to raise pitch. Asking someone to lower their voice requires reducing cricothyroid activity. It is innervated by the external laryngeal nerve (superior laryngeal nerve).<br><br>Take Notes: cricothyroid → tenses/lengthens cord → raises pitch | PCA → abducts cord (opens glottis) | Thyroarytenoid → shortens/relaxes cord (lowers pitch) | Cricothyroid = pitch control = external laryngeal nerve supply."},
/*120*/ {"q":"A Pap smear of lady done which shows basement membrane is intact. N/C ratio increases. Showing dysplasia. CIS. Ratio and Dysplasia. Which of the following is regarding true about median nerve in brachial artery in cubital fossa. Which of following is true regarding. Regarding Median nerve. Regarding Median nerve. Which of the following is most true of the following is true about median nerve regarding cubital fossa. A Pap smear of lady done which shows. CIS. Ans: C. Post-term pregnancy by WHO regarding is called at:","o":["Jugular venous pressure","Medial 2 lumbricles are fractured","Anterior spinal artery","Inferior vena cava"],"a":0,"e":"Raised jugular venous pressure (JVP) is the cardinal sign of right heart failure and elevated central venous pressure. It reflects the pressure in the superior vena cava/right atrium, visible as jugular venous distension at >45° of elevation.<br><br>Take Notes: raised JVP → right heart failure + cardiac tamponade + superior vena cava obstruction | JVP > 3-4 cm above sternal angle = abnormal | Kussmaul sign → JVP rises on inspiration (constrictive pericarditis) | JVP = right atrial pressure = central venous pressure indicator."},
/*121*/ {"q":"An Adult presented with fever, sore throat, posterior cervical lymphadenopathy. Blood smear is most likely following. Which diagnosis:","o":["HIV","B-Cell Lymphoma","Infectious Mononucleosis","Infective Endocarditis"],"a":2,"e":"Fever + sore throat + posterior cervical lymphadenopathy + atypical lymphocytes on smear = infectious mononucleosis (EBV). Monospot test (heterophile antibodies) confirms the diagnosis.<br><br>Take Notes: EBV mononucleosis → fever + pharyngitis + posterior cervical LN + atypical lymphocytes | Monospot (heterophile antibody) → positive | Posterior cervical nodes → EBV (vs anterior = bacterial tonsillitis) | EBV = posterior cervical LN = atypical lymphocytes = mononucleosis."},
/*122*/ {"q":"Vein accompanying left circumflex artery is which of following — Lymph nodes involved in Carcinoma of lower lip arc:","o":["Adult T cell Leukemia","Infectious Endocarditis","B-Cell Lymphoma","Isoniazid neuropathy is reversed by"],"a":3,"e":"Isoniazid (INH) causes peripheral neuropathy by interfering with pyridoxine (Vitamin B6) metabolism. This is prevented and treated by pyridoxine (Vitamin B6) supplementation. INH inhibits pyridoxine phosphokinase.<br><br>Take Notes: INH neuropathy → pyridoxine (B6) deficiency | Prevention/treatment → B6 supplementation | INH also hepatotoxic (check LFTs) | Isoniazid = B6 deficiency neuropathy = reverse with pyridoxine."},
/*123*/ {"q":"A student of Final year MBBS witnessing Surgery for the first time collapsed in OT due to:","o":["Vit B1","Vit B2","Vit B5","Dec peripheral resistance"],"a":3,"e":"Medical students fainting in the operating theatre is a classic vasovagal (neurocardiogenic) syncope — emotional stress triggers vagal activation causing bradycardia and peripheral vasodilation (decreased peripheral resistance), reducing cerebral perfusion.<br><br>Take Notes: vasovagal syncope → ↓peripheral resistance + bradycardia → cerebral hypoperfusion | Triggered by emotional stress/pain/prolonged standing | Dec peripheral resistance = vasodilation = the vasovagal mechanism | Dec peripheral resistance = OT fainting = vasovagal syncope."},
/*124*/ {"q":"A student of Final year MBBS. Vasovagal. Dec peripheral resistance. An alcoholic presented with Dysphagia to solids as well as dysphagia. Valvular disease. On Examination with Raised Checks and Raised Jugular venous pressure, Dysphagia. On examination presented with history of Rheumatic valvular disease. What is the most likely cause of Dysphagia. Vasovagal. Properties of baroreceptors. Vasovagal property of baroreceptors:","o":["Dec venous compliance","Vasovagal property of baroreceptors","Dec Map","E (Vasovagal) > TPR"],"a":3,"e":"Baroreceptors (carotid sinus and aortic arch) respond to increased BP by increasing vagal tone (slowing HR, decreasing vasomotor tone) and decreasing sympathetic output — the vasovagal mechanism. Decreased MAP stimulates baroreceptors to increase sympathetic tone.<br><br>Take Notes: baroreceptors → respond to ↑BP by ↑vagal tone + ↓sympathetic | ↓BP → ↑sympathetic (reflex tachycardia + vasoconstriction) | Baroreceptor = the acute BP reflex arc | Vasovagal = baroreceptor-mediated = HR and vasomotor reflex."},
/*125*/ {"q":"Emissary veins pass through:","o":["Foramen Ovale","Foramen Rotundum","Foramen Lacurum","Foramen Cecum"],"a":0,"e":"Emissary veins pass through skull foramina connecting the intracranial dural venous sinuses with extracranial veins. They can pass through the foramen ovale (connecting cavernous sinus to pterygoid plexus) and other skull foramina, allowing bidirectional spread of infection.<br><br>Take Notes: emissary veins → pass through skull foramina (foramen ovale, mastoid foramen, parietal foramen) | Connect dural sinuses ↔ extracranial veins | Valveless → allow retrograde infection spread | Foramen ovale = cavernous sinus to pterygoid plexus = emissary vein route."},
/*126*/ {"q":"Pregnant lady with 41 weeks OS anxious days Post term pregnancy. What term pregnancy requested for induction of labour by WHO is called at:","o":["Gastrocolic artery","Splenic artery","Left gastric artery","Gastroepiploic artery"],"a":2,"e":"Post-term pregnancy (>42 weeks) complicates management; WHO recommends induction at 41-42 weeks. The left gastric artery (from coeliac axis) supplies the lesser curvature of the stomach — this question conflates two topics; per the source the answer is left gastric artery in context of gastric blood supply.<br><br>Take Notes: left gastric artery → lesser curvature + lower oesophagus (coeliac branch) | Right gastric → lesser curvature (hepatic proper branch) | Post-term induction → WHO recommends at 41-42 weeks | Left gastric = lesser curvature = coeliac branch."},
/*127*/ {"q":"Numbness of lower lip medial part after dental extraction. Which nerve? Inferior alveolar nerve. Part after dental extraction. A patient had RTA. Neck damage. Vertebra. Posterior wall of stomach. In perforation of stomach which artery is involved?","o":["Gastrocolic artery","Splenic artery","Left gastric artery","Gastroepiploic artery"],"a":1,"e":"The posterior wall of the stomach is in direct contact with the splenic artery (which runs along the upper border of the pancreas to the splenic hilum). Posterior gastric ulcer perforation can erode into the splenic artery or cause bleeding into the lesser sac.<br><br>Take Notes: posterior stomach wall → splenic artery at risk | Left gastric → lesser curvature (anterior + posterior) | Gastroduodenal artery → posterior duodenal wall (D1) | Posterior stomach perforation = splenic artery = the erosion risk."},
/*128*/ {"q":"A pregnant lady in her first trimester with Hb 9g/dl, MCV 58. Investigation to be done?","o":["Bone marrow Biopsy","HbA & HbF","HbA2","HBA2 & Ferritin in normal range"],"a":3,"e":"Microcytic anaemia (MCV 58) in pregnancy with normal-high ferritin (distinguishing from iron deficiency) requires HbA2 measurement to confirm thalassaemia trait. Ferritin must be checked to exclude IDA first; if normal, HbA2 > 3.5% = beta-thalassaemia trait.<br><br>Take Notes: microcytic + normal/high ferritin in pregnancy → thalassaemia trait | HbA2 >3.5% → beta-thalassaemia trait | Ferritin low → iron deficiency (treat with iron first) | HbA2 + ferritin = the thalassaemia screening pair."},
/*129*/ {"q":"An alcoholic presented with Dysphagia to solids as well as liquids. Valvular disease — Rheumatic. Most likely cause of Dysphagia:","o":["Adenocarcinoma","Melanoma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Basal cell carcinoma"],"a":0,"e":"A patient with rheumatic heart disease (enlarged left atrium from mitral stenosis) can develop dysphagia from LA compression of the oesophagus. However, progressive dysphagia solids → liquids in an alcoholic = oesophageal carcinoma (most likely adenocarcinoma from Barrett's in alcohol + GERD context).<br><br>Take Notes: alcoholic + progressive dysphagia solids→liquids → oesophageal CA | Middle oesophagus + smoking/alcohol → SCC | Lower oesophagus + GERD/Barrett's → adenocarcinoma | Adenocarcinoma = lower oesophagus = GERD/alcohol context."},
/*130*/ {"q":"Patient with history of Rheumatic Valvular disease. Mitral Stenosis Presented. Dysphagia. On Examination Raised JVP and Dysphagia. Which of the following can be the cause of dysphagia in this patient?","o":["Right ventricle","Left ventricle","Right atrium","Left atrium"],"a":3,"e":"Mitral stenosis causes left atrial dilation. The enlarged LA lies directly posterior to the oesophagus and compresses it, causing dysphagia. This is detected as posterior oesophageal indentation on barium swallow.<br><br>Take Notes: mitral stenosis → dilated LA → posterior oesophageal compression → dysphagia | Barium swallow → posterior oesophageal indentation | Dysphagia + rheumatic heart disease → think dilated LA | Left atrium = the cardiac dysphagia cause."},
/*131*/ {"q":"In Perforation of Stomach Posterior wall Artery. Ans: B — Splenic artery. In perforation of stomach which artery is involved. In Posterior wall. Ans: B (Splenic artery). A patient of perforation of stomach. In perforation of stomach which artery is involved:","o":["Gastrocolic artery","Splenic artery","Left gastric artery","Gastroepiploic artery"],"a":1,"e":"Posterior gastric wall perforation risks the splenic artery, which runs along the superior pancreatic border in direct contact with the posterior gastric wall. Erosion causes life-threatening haemorrhage into the lesser sac.<br><br>Take Notes: posterior stomach wall → splenic artery (runs along upper pancreatic border) | Anterior stomach → free peritoneal spillage | Posterior duodenal wall → gastroduodenal artery | Posterior stomach perforation = splenic artery = lesser sac haemorrhage."},
/*132*/ {"q":"Ureter can be damaged while ligating ovarian artery at:","o":["Pelvic Brim","Pelvic Outlet","Sacral hatus","Seera hatus"],"a":0,"e":"The ureter crosses the pelvic brim at the bifurcation of the common iliac artery. The ovarian vessels cross the ureter anteriorly at the pelvic brim. When ligating the infundibulopelvic ligament (containing ovarian vessels), the ureter directly beneath is at risk.<br><br>Take Notes: ureter at risk → pelvic brim (where ovarian vessels cross anteriorly) | Also at risk → where uterine artery crosses ureter ('water under bridge') | 'Water under the bridge' = uterine artery over ureter | Pelvic brim = ovarian vessel ligation = ureter danger."},
/*133*/ {"q":"Blood supply of proximal part of duodenum is supplied by gastro duodenal artery while distal part of duodenum is supplied by gastro duodenal artery:","o":["Pancreatic artery","Gastro duodenal artery","Inferior pancreaticoduodenal artery","Superior mesenteric artery"],"a":2,"e":"The distal duodenum (3rd and 4th parts) is supplied by the inferior pancreaticoduodenal artery — a branch of the SMA. The proximal duodenum is supplied by the superior pancreaticoduodenal artery (from gastroduodenal/celiac).<br><br>Take Notes: proximal duodenum (1st-2nd) → superior pancreaticoduodenal (celiac/GDA) | Distal duodenum (3rd-4th) → inferior pancreaticoduodenal (SMA) | Watershed → junction of 2nd and 3rd parts | Inferior pancreaticoduodenal = distal duodenum = SMA branch."},
/*134*/ {"q":"20 year girl annual lower abdominal pain on examination there is imperforate hymen ring? Monthly lower abdominal pain. On examination there is imperforate hymen ring:","o":["Transverse vaginal septum","Bicornuate uterus","Cervical atresia","Imperforate hymen"],"a":3,"e":"Cyclic monthly lower abdominal pain with a bluish bulging membrane at the introitus (haematocolpos) in a teenager with primary amenorrhoea = imperforate hymen. Blood accumulates (haematocolpos) causing cyclical pain.<br><br>Take Notes: imperforate hymen → haematocolpos (blood in vagina) + haematometra | Cyclical pain + primary amenorrhoea + bulging membrane = classic | Treatment → hymenotomy | Imperforate hymen = haematocolpos = the cyclical pain cause."},
/*135*/ {"q":"Patient after RTA Fracture of 9th rib left side Hypotension cause is:","o":["Cervical atresia","Transverse vaginal septum","Gall bladder Rupture","Spleen Rupture"],"a":3,"e":"Left lower rib (9th-11th) fractures cause splenic rupture — the spleen lies under the left lower ribs and is the most commonly injured solid organ in abdominal trauma. It causes hypotension from intraperitoneal haemorrhage.<br><br>Take Notes: left lower rib fracture (9th-11th) → splenic rupture → intraperitoneal haemorrhage | Right lower ribs → liver injury | Spleen = most commonly injured solid organ in trauma | Left 9th rib + hypotension = splenic rupture."},
/*136*/ {"q":"Spleen located on left side at the level of 9-11 Ribs. In Alzheimer disease finding will be:","o":["Hypertrophy of brain","Hypoplasia of brain","Hyperplasia of brain","Atrophy of brain"],"a":3,"e":"Alzheimer's disease is characterised by generalised cortical atrophy, particularly in the hippocampus and temporal/parietal lobes, causing the classic 'knife-blade' gyri and widened sulci on imaging. Senile plaques (amyloid-beta) and neurofibrillary tangles (tau) are the histological hallmarks.<br><br>Take Notes: Alzheimer's → cortical atrophy (hippocampus + temporal parietal) | Amyloid-beta plaques + tau tangles (neurofibrillary) | Knife-blade gyri + wide sulci on imaging | Atrophy = Alzheimer's = the macroscopic finding."},
/*137*/ {"q":"Vitamin K deficiency causes increase in:","o":["PT","BT","CT","None"],"a":0,"e":"Vitamin K deficiency prolongs PT (prothrombin time) — Factor VII has the shortest half-life and falls first, prolonging the extrinsic pathway. APTT also prolonged eventually.<br><br>Take Notes: Vitamin K deficiency → ↑PT (Factor VII falls first, shortest t½) | Also ↑APTT (factors IX, X, II) | Bleeding time → unaffected (platelet function intact) | PT = earliest + most sensitive Vitamin K deficiency test."},
/*138*/ {"q":"A patient cannot recognize objects with close eye. Lesion is in:","o":["Neocortex","Primary somaesthetic area","Secondary somaesthetic area","Frontal cortex"],"a":2,"e":"Astereognosis (inability to recognise objects by touch with intact primary sensation) indicates secondary somatosensory cortex (S2) lesion in the parietal operculum.<br><br>Take Notes: astereognosis → secondary somatosensory cortex (S2) | Primary somatosensory (S1) → receives raw sensory input (if damaged → anaesthesia, not astereognosis) | S2 lesion = object recognition failure by touch | Astereognosis = S2 = parietal operculum."},
/*139*/ {"q":"Sympathomimetic drug is which one following:","o":["Propanolol","Amphetamine","Nabivolol","Alfazocin"],"a":1,"e":"Amphetamine is an indirect sympathomimetic — it releases norepinephrine and dopamine from presynaptic terminals and blocks reuptake, causing CNS stimulation and peripheral sympathetic effects.<br><br>Take Notes: amphetamine → indirect sympathomimetic (NE + DA release + reuptake inhibition) | Propranolol/nebivolol → beta-blockers (sympatholytics) | Alfuzosin → alpha-1 blocker | Amphetamine = only sympathomimetic in the list."},
/*140*/ {"q":"6 year old girl presented OPD with excessive facial and chest hairs, adult size external genitalia and deepening voice. Siblings died from same condition. Which enzyme deficiency?","o":["17-alpha hydroxylase deficiency","21 hydroxylase deficiency","11 B-hydroxylase deficiency","22 hydroxylase deficiency"],"a":1,"e":"21-hydroxylase deficiency (most common CAH, 90%) causes androgen excess with virilisation in females — facial hair, clitoral enlargement, deepened voice. Salt-wasting form is life-threatening.<br><br>Take Notes: 21-hydroxylase deficiency → most common CAH → virilisation in females | 11-beta-hydroxylase → virilisation + hypertension | 17-alpha-hydroxylase → no sex hormones + hypertension | 21-OHase = CAH = starts with 2 = virilisation + salt-wasting."},
/*141*/ {"q":"HSV 2 causes which of following:","o":["CA Cervix","CA Endometrium","CA Ovary","CA Breast"],"a":0,"e":"HSV-2 acts as a cofactor for cervical carcinoma alongside HPV 16/18. HSV-2 promotes oncogenic transformation in HPV-infected cervical cells.<br><br>Take Notes: HSV-2 → cervical CA (cofactor with HPV) | HPV 16/18 → primary cervical CA cause | HSV-1 → herpes labialis + keratitis + encephalitis | HSV-2 = genital = cervical CA risk factor."},
/*142*/ {"q":"Conducting system of heart is located in:","o":["Sulcus terminalis","Moderator band","Sub epicardium","Sub endocardium"],"a":3,"e":"The cardiac conducting system (SA node, AV node, His bundle, Purkinje fibres) lies in the subendocardial layer, allowing direct electrical contact with ventricular myocardium.<br><br>Take Notes: conducting system → subendocardial position | SA node → sulcus terminalis (right atrium) | AV node → Koch's triangle subendocardium | Subendocardium = conducting system location."},
/*143*/ {"q":"Heat loss is controlled by:","o":["Vasoconstriction of Skin vessels","Vasodilation of Skin vessels","Anterior Hypothalamus","Preoptic area"],"a":3,"e":"The preoptic area of the anterior hypothalamus is the thermostat for heat dissipation — it triggers cutaneous vasodilation and sweating when body temperature rises.<br><br>Take Notes: preoptic/anterior hypothalamus → heat LOSS centre | Posterior hypothalamus → heat CONSERVATION (cold response) | Vasodilation of skin → mechanism (controlled by preoptic area) | Preoptic area = thermostat = heat dissipation centre."},
/*144*/ {"q":"Female with fever sore throat and 60% B lymphocytes. B and T lymphocytes normal percentage in blood?","o":["B lymphocytes 50%","T lymphocytes 80-90% and B lymphocytes 10-20%","B lymphocytes 90% and T lymphocytes 10%","T lymphocytes 20%"],"a":1,"e":"Normal peripheral blood lymphocytes: T cells 70-80%, B cells 10-20%, NK cells 5-15%. EBV mononucleosis produces reactive T lymphocytes (atypical lymphocytes).<br><br>Take Notes: normal blood: T cells 70-80% + B cells 10-20% | EBV → atypical lymphocytes = reactive T cells | NK cells → ~5-15% | T:B ratio ≈ 7:1-8:1 in peripheral blood."},
/*145*/ {"q":"In quiet respiration muscle which increase vertical diameter of thorax:","o":["Diaphragm","External intercostal","Internal intercostal","Accessory muscles"],"a":0,"e":"The diaphragm increases the vertical thoracic diameter during quiet inspiration by descending, providing ~75% of tidal volume.<br><br>Take Notes: diaphragm → vertical diameter increase (descends) | External intercostals → AP diameter increase (bucket handle) | Accessory muscles → only in forced inspiration | Diaphragm = 75% quiet tidal volume = vertical expansion."},
/*146*/ {"q":"Heinz bodies are found in:","o":["Hereditary spherocytosis","G6PD deficiency","Pyruvate kinase deficiency","Ciehosis"],"a":1,"e":"Heinz bodies are denatured haemoglobin precipitates forming in G6PD-deficient RBCs under oxidative stress (drugs, infection). Splenic macrophages remove them, creating bite cells.<br><br>Take Notes: Heinz bodies → G6PD deficiency (oxidative haemolysis) | Bite cells → after Heinz body removal by spleen | Spherocytes → hereditary spherocytosis | Heinz bodies = G6PD = denatured haemoglobin precipitates."},
/*147*/ {"q":"Development of breast alveoli and lobules is function of:","o":["Estrogen","Prolactin","Oxytocin","Progesterone"],"a":3,"e":"Progesterone (with prolactin) drives lobulo-alveolar development. Oestrogen stimulates ductal growth. Oxytocin causes milk ejection; prolactin causes milk synthesis.<br><br>Take Notes: progesterone → alveoli + lobule development | Oestrogen → ductal growth | Prolactin → milk synthesis | Oxytocin → milk ejection (letdown) | Progesterone = alveolar development = secretory unit formation."},
/*148*/ {"q":"A patient exhibits signs of Myasthenia Gravis. What is best confirmatory test?","o":["Biopsy","EMG","Edrophonium","Ach receptors antibodies"],"a":1,"e":"EMG showing decremental response on repetitive nerve stimulation is the electrophysiological confirmation of MG. Anti-AChR antibodies are specific but 15% of MG is seronegative.<br><br>Take Notes: MG confirmatory → EMG (decremental response on repetitive stimulation) | Anti-AChR → specific but seronegative in 15% | Edrophonium test → clinical (brief improvement) | EMG decremental = the electrophysiological MG proof."},
/*149*/ {"q":"Good doctor patient relationship requires:","o":["Having sound medical knowledge","Updating skills","Show authority","Active listening"],"a":3,"e":"Active listening is the foundation of the doctor-patient relationship, ensuring patients feel heard, improving history accuracy and therapeutic compliance.<br><br>Take Notes: good doctor-patient relationship → active listening (most important) | Authority → undermines trust | Medical knowledge → necessary but not sufficient | Active listening = therapeutic communication = the foundation."},
/*150*/ {"q":"Increase extracellular calcium causes which of these?","o":["Systolic arrest","Diastolic arrest","Both arrests","No significant effect on heart"],"a":0,"e":"Hypercalcaemia locks the heart in sustained systolic contraction. This is opposite to hyperkalaemia, which causes diastolic arrest.<br><br>Take Notes: hypercalcaemia → systolic arrest (sustained contraction) | Hyperkalaemia → diastolic arrest | Memory: Ca = contraction = systolic; K = relaxation = diastolic | Systolic arrest = hypercalcaemia = calcium excess."}
,
/*151*/ {"q":"Pituitary tumor which causes most commonly:","o":["Increase Dopamine","Increase Prolactin","Decrease Dopamine","Decrease Prolactin"],"a":1,"e":"Prolactinoma is the most common pituitary adenoma (~40%). It causes hyperprolactinaemia with galactorrhoea, amenorrhoea, and infertility in women; hypogonadism in men.<br><br>Take Notes: prolactinoma → most common pituitary adenoma | Hyperprolactinaemia → galactorrhoea + amenorrhoea (women) | Treatment → cabergoline (D2 agonist, suppresses prolactin) | Prolactin ↑ = prolactinoma = most common pituitary tumour."},
/*152*/ {"q":"A lady came into opd with raised serum electrolyte K. A lady came into opd with raised serum electrolyte K. Lady came with raised serum electrolyte k. Increase K. Thiazide Diuretics. Site of action of Thiazide Diuretics:","o":["Distal Convoluted Tubule","Proximal Convoluted Tubule","Thick Ascending limb of loop of henie","Descending Limb of loop of henie"],"a":0,"e":"Thiazide diuretics block the Na+/Cl- cotransporter in the early distal convoluted tubule (DCT), reducing sodium reabsorption and causing natriuresis and diuresis.<br><br>Take Notes: thiazides → early DCT (Na+/Cl- cotransporter) | Loop diuretics → thick ascending limb (NKCC2 transporter) | Spironolactone → collecting duct (aldosterone antagonist) | DCT = thiazide site = distal convoluted tubule."},
/*153*/ {"q":"A Surgeon is performing surgery and a vessel is damaged leading to whole operative field pooled with blood. A vessel is damaged. Most likely damaged is:","o":["Splenic artery","Descending Limb","Proximal Convoluted Tubule","Distal Convoluted Tubule"],"a":0,"e":"During abdominal surgery, the splenic artery (tortuous, running along the superior pancreatic border) is a commonly injured vessel causing massive haemorrhage. Its proximity to the pancreatic tail makes it vulnerable during pancreatectomy and splenectomy.<br><br>Take Notes: abdominal surgery massive bleed → splenic artery (pancreatic border) at risk | Splenic artery → tortuous, along upper pancreas | Portal vein → posterior pancreatic neck | Splenic artery = operative field flooding = the likely vessel."},
/*154*/ {"q":"Tip Of Scapula Level?","o":["T8","Aorta","T11","T9"],"a":2,"e":"The inferior angle (tip) of the scapula lies at the level of T7-T8 vertebra (some sources T7, others T8). Clinically it is used as a landmark for intercostal nerve blocks and pleural procedures. Per source answer: T11 is listed but T7-T8 is the standard anatomical level.<br><br>Take Notes: tip/inferior angle of scapula → T7-T8 vertebral level (standard) | Source here states T11 | Medial scapular border → T2-T7 | Inferior angle = T7-T8 = intercostal landmark."},
/*155*/ {"q":"A pregnant lady of 3rd trimester having unchanged endometrium:","o":["T10","T11","T7","T8"],"a":3,"e":"In the third trimester, rising progesterone and oestrogen maintain the decidualised endometrium (now called decidua), preventing menstruation. The endometrium remains thickened and transformed — not shed. T8 vertebral level is the xiphoid process landmark, separate from this question.<br><br>Take Notes: 3rd trimester endometrium → maintained as decidua (progesterone) | Progesterone → prevents endometrial shedding throughout pregnancy | Oestrogen → stimulates endometrial growth | Decidua = pregnant endometrium = progesterone maintained."},
/*156*/ {"q":"In late pregnancy endometrium sensitive for:","o":["Growth hormone","Estrogen","PTH","Cortisol"],"a":1,"e":"In late pregnancy, the endometrium (decidua) is maximally sensitive to oestrogen, which promotes further endometrial proliferation and prepares the uterus for labour. Oestrogen also sensitises the uterus to oxytocin at term.<br><br>Take Notes: late pregnancy endometrium → most sensitive to oestrogen | Oestrogen → sensitises uterus to oxytocin (upregulates oxytocin receptors) | Progesterone → maintains pregnancy (prevents contractions) | Oestrogen = late pregnancy uterine sensitisation."},
/*157*/ {"q":"A 23 Year old primigravida presented in 2nd department on examination the sacral promontory was not reachable. Ischial spines were narrow and the pelvic arch was most likely:","o":["Platypelloid pelvis","Anthropoid pelvis","Gynecoid pelvis","Android pelvis"],"a":1,"e":"Non-reachable sacral promontory (adequate AP diameter) + narrow ischial spines (reduced transverse) + prominent pelvic arch = anthropoid pelvis (oval shaped, AP diameter > transverse). This is the second most common female pelvis type.<br><br>Take Notes: anthropoid pelvis → oval (AP > transverse), narrow ischial spines | Gynecoid → round (most common female, best for delivery) | Android → heart-shaped (narrow, poor for delivery) | Platypelloid → flat (wide transverse, short AP) | Anthropoid = non-reachable promontory = oval."},
/*158*/ {"q":"Which of the following is locally malignant tumor?","o":["Promontory - Contracted Pelvis","Fingers not Reachable to Sacral","Platypelloid pelvis","Android pelvis"],"a":1,"e":"BCC (basal cell carcinoma) is the classic locally malignant tumour — it invades locally and destroys tissues but almost never metastasises (<0.1%). It is the most common skin cancer in fair-skinned individuals.<br><br>Take Notes: BCC → locally invasive, almost never metastasises | SCC → locally invasive + can metastasise | Melanoma → highly metastatic | BCC = locally malignant = non-metastasising skin cancer."},
/*159*/ {"q":"Child with machinery murmur likely due to:","o":["Melanoma","Squamous Cell Carcinoma","Adenoid cystic carcinoma","Ameloblastoma"],"a":0,"e":"A continuous 'machinery' murmur in a child = patent ductus arteriosus (PDA). Blood shunts from high-pressure aorta to lower-pressure pulmonary artery continuously (systole + diastole), creating the characteristic machinery sound at the left upper sternal border.<br><br>Take Notes: machinery murmur → PDA (patent ductus arteriosus) | Continuous murmur heard at left upper sternal border | Indomethacin → closes PDA (inhibits prostaglandins) | Machinery murmur = PDA = continuous shunt sound."},
/*160*/ {"q":"50 years female, diabetic for 20 years, abdominal distension after meals, which of the following drug is most suitable for treatment?","o":["Ondansetron","Bismuth","Metoclopramide","Sucralfate"],"a":2,"e":"Diabetic gastroparesis causes delayed gastric emptying and post-meal distension. Metoclopramide (D2 antagonist + 5-HT4 agonist) is the first-line prokinetic agent, stimulating gastric motility and accelerating gastric emptying.<br><br>Take Notes: diabetic gastroparesis → metoclopramide (prokinetic, D2 antagonist) | Also domperidone (fewer CNS effects) | Ondansetron → anti-emetic (5-HT3 antagonist), not prokinetic | Metoclopramide = diabetic gastroparesis = first-line prokinetic."},
/*161*/ {"q":"A young female, diabetic for 20 years, abdominal distension. Muscularis Mucosae:","o":["Mucosa","Lamina Propria","Muscularis Mucosae","Muscularis Externa"],"a":2,"e":"The muscularis mucosae is the thin smooth muscle layer within the mucosa (beneath the lamina propria). It separates the mucosa from the submucosa and produces small mucosal movements to increase absorption surface contact.<br><br>Take Notes: mucosa layers → epithelium → lamina propria → muscularis mucosae | Muscularis externa → outer muscle (circular + longitudinal) | Muscularis mucosae → separates mucosa from submucosa | Muscularis mucosae = innermost muscle layer = within mucosa."},
/*162*/ {"q":"A patient having abdominal distension and tachycardia and Bp 80/60 after Laparotomy due to which of these:","o":["Anaphylactic Shock","Septic Shock","Hypovolaemic Shock","Cardiogenic Shock"],"a":1,"e":"Post-laparotomy hypotension with tachycardia suggests either hypovolaemic (blood loss) or septic shock. The context of abdominal surgery + Bp 80/60 + tachycardia post-laparotomy most commonly indicates septic shock from bowel contamination or anastomotic leak.<br><br>Take Notes: post-laparotomy hypotension + tachycardia → septic shock (bowel contamination) or hypovolaemia | Septic → distributive (vasodilated, warm) | Hypovolaemic → cold, clammy, reduced CVP | Post-laparotomy + fever = septic shock until proven otherwise."},
/*163*/ {"q":"Deep structure in popliteal fossa:","o":["Tibial nerve","Common peroneal nerve","Popliteal vein","Popliteal artery"],"a":3,"e":"The popliteal fossa contents from superficial to deep: tibial nerve → popliteal vein → popliteal artery (deepest, on posterior knee capsule).<br><br>Take Notes: popliteal fossa (superficial to deep): nerve → vein → artery (NVA) | Popliteal artery = deepest | This order explains why knee dislocations risk arterial injury | Popliteal artery = deepest = the NVA rule."},
/*164*/ {"q":"Deep structure in popliteal fossa. Ans: A. Mixed blood sample obtained:","o":["Popliteal vein","Right ventricular","Common peroneal nerve","Right atrium"],"a":3,"e":"A mixed venous blood sample (showing true mixed venous oxygen saturation) is obtained from the right atrium or pulmonary artery, where blood from the superior and inferior vena cava has fully mixed. This is used in cardiac output calculations.<br><br>Take Notes: mixed venous blood → right atrium or pulmonary artery (fully mixed) | SvO2 normal → 75% | Low SvO2 → increased O2 extraction (↓CO or ↑demand) | Right atrium = mixed venous sampling = true mixed blood."},
/*165*/ {"q":"Which one of the following is highest at apex of lungs:","o":["V/Q ratio","Ventilation","Dead Space","Perfusion"],"a":0,"e":"At the apex of the lung, both ventilation and perfusion are lower than at the base due to gravity, but perfusion falls more than ventilation. Therefore the V/Q ratio is highest at the apex (>1) and lowest at the base (<1).<br><br>Take Notes: apex → V/Q ratio highest (>1) — perfusion ↓↓ more than ventilation | Base → V/Q lowest (<1) — perfusion ↑↑ more | Normal mean V/Q → 0.8 | V/Q highest = apex = best matched alveoli."},
/*166*/ {"q":"Regional arterial PCO2 is highest at base. V/Q base apex. Blood flow. Ventilation. Damage to glossopharyngeal nerve leads to loss of which of the following taste sensation?","o":["Sweet","Salt","Sour","Bitter"],"a":3,"e":"The glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX) carries taste from the posterior 1/3 of the tongue. The posterior tongue is more sensitive to bitter taste. CN IX also carries the gag reflex and general sensation from the posterior tongue/pharynx.<br><br>Take Notes: CN IX → taste from posterior 1/3 tongue (bitter predominant) | CN VII (chorda tympani) → taste from anterior 2/3 (sweet, salt, sour) | CN IX + X → pharyngeal + epiglottic taste | Bitter = posterior tongue = CN IX."},
/*167*/ {"q":"A patient Para 8 with prolapse and cervix at intro. Injury damage is:","o":["Uterosacral ligament","Transverse cervical ligament","Broad ligament","Round ligament"],"a":1,"e":"Uterine prolapse results from weakening of the cardinal (transverse cervical/Mackenrodt's) ligaments — the primary supports suspending the cervix and upper vagina. Damage from childbirth (especially grand multiparity) leads to prolapse.<br><br>Take Notes: uterine prolapse → cardinal/transverse cervical ligament (Mackenrodt's) damage | Uterosacral → secondary support (posterior) | Round ligament → maintains anteversion (not prolapse prevention) | Cardinal ligament = primary uterine support = prolapse cause when damaged."},
/*168*/ {"q":"Oxyhaemoglobin curve shifts to:","o":["Haldane effect","Bohr effect","Bohn effect","None of the above"],"a":1,"e":"The Bohr effect describes the right shift of the O2-haemoglobin dissociation curve with increased PCO2 or H+ (decreased pH) — reducing O2 affinity and promoting O2 delivery to active tissues. The Haldane effect is the reverse: O2 binding to Hb reduces CO2-carrying capacity.<br><br>Take Notes: Bohr effect → CO2/H+ → right shift → ↓O2 affinity → better tissue O2 delivery | Haldane effect → O2 binding → ↓CO2 carrying capacity | CADET face right → right shift causes | Bohr = the O2 delivery effect."},
/*169*/ {"q":"Which condition Gastro Oesophageal junction is:","o":["Pylorus","Gastroesophageal junction","Gastrocolic junction","None of the above"],"a":1,"e":"The gastroesophageal junction (GEJ/cardia) marks the transition from oesophageal squamous epithelium to gastric columnar epithelium (the Z-line). Barrett's oesophagus occurs when columnar metaplasia extends proximally at this junction.<br><br>Take Notes: GEJ = Z-line = squamocolumnar junction | Barrett's oesophagus → columnar metaplasia at GEJ | GEJ → GERD + adenocarcinoma association | Z-line = GEJ = the squamocolumnar boundary."},
/*170*/ {"q":"Muscle in the greater sciatic foramen:","o":["Obturator Internus","Gemellus inferior","Piriformis","Obturator Externus"],"a":2,"e":"The piriformis muscle exits through the greater sciatic foramen and is the key landmark. It divides the foramen into a supra-piriform (superior gluteal vessels/nerve) and infra-piriform (sciatic nerve, pudendal nerve, inferior gluteal) portion.<br><br>Take Notes: piriformis → exits through greater sciatic foramen | Above piriformis → superior gluteal nerve + vessels | Below piriformis → sciatic nerve + inferior gluteal + pudendal | Piriformis = the greater sciatic foramen muscle landmark."},
/*171*/ {"q":"Regarding fecal incontinence after vaginal delivery investigate:","o":["Anal manometry","MRI","Pudendal nerve stimulation test","Anorectal manometry"],"a":0,"e":"Anal manometry is the gold standard investigation for faecal incontinence post-delivery — it measures resting pressure (internal sphincter) and squeeze pressure (external sphincter), identifying sphincter dysfunction.<br><br>Take Notes: faecal incontinence investigation → anal manometry (gold standard) | Endoanal ultrasound → anatomical sphincter integrity (identifies tears) | Pudendal nerve terminal motor latency → nerve damage assessment | Anal manometry = function; endoanal US = anatomy."},
/*172*/ {"q":"Pancreatic injury secretion goes into:","o":["Greater sac","Lesser sac","Sub pancreatic space","Left paracolic gutter"],"a":1,"e":"The pancreas lies retroperitoneally, directly posterior to the lesser sac (omental bursa). Pancreatic fluid leaks preferentially into the lesser sac, forming a pseudocyst.<br><br>Take Notes: pancreas → retroperitoneal → lies posterior to lesser sac | Pancreatic pseudocyst → lesser sac | Greater sac involvement → if lesser sac ruptures | Lesser sac = pancreatic pseudocyst = the initial fluid collection site."},
/*173*/ {"q":"Bone scan necessary for:","o":["Neurovascular bundle lies at","Squamous cell carcinoma","Melanoma","Retinoblastoma"],"a":3,"e":"Retinoblastoma (paediatric intraocular malignancy) requires bone scan as part of staging because it can metastasise to bone. The Rb1 gene mutation on chromosome 13 is the tumour suppressor involved.<br><br>Take Notes: retinoblastoma → Rb1 gene (chromosome 13) | Staging → bone scan (bone metastasis) | Bilateral/familial → germline mutation | Retinoblastoma = bone scan = the paediatric eye tumour."},
/*174*/ {"q":"Neurovascular bundle lies at:","o":["Between external and internal","Lower end of interosseal space","Upper border of rib","Lower border of rib"],"a":3,"e":"The intercostal neurovascular bundle (vein, artery, nerve — VAN from superior to inferior) runs in the costal groove along the lower border of each rib. Safe procedures require instruments to be introduced above the upper border of the rib below.<br><br>Take Notes: intercostal NVB → lower border of rib (costal groove) | Safe approach → above upper border of lower rib | Order (superior to inferior) → vein → artery → nerve (VAN) | Lower border of rib = NVB = the danger zone for chest procedures."},
/*175*/ {"q":"In zone 1 of the lung what happens?","o":["Dead space high","Dead space low","Shunting high","Shunting low"],"a":0,"e":"Zone 1 (apex) has alveolar pressure > arterial pressure > venous pressure — no blood flow during part of the cardiac cycle, creating physiological dead space (ventilated but not perfused). Dead space is highest at the apex.<br><br>Take Notes: Zone 1 (apex) → dead space (ventilated, not perfused) | Zone 2 → ventilation = perfusion (V/Q ≈ 1) | Zone 3 (base) → shunting (perfused > ventilated) | Zone 1 = apex = dead space = high V/Q."},
/*176*/ {"q":"46XX female child with ambiguous genitalia, what is the karyotype?","o":["Fetal aromatic deficiency","Testicular feminization syndrome","Zone inhibition in High dead space","46XXX abnormality"],"a":0,"e":"A 46,XX female with ambiguous genitalia is most commonly caused by congenital adrenal hyperplasia (CAH — 21-hydroxylase deficiency) causing androgen excess virilising the external genitalia. Aromatase deficiency is another cause (foetal aromatase deficiency → androgens from placenta cannot be converted to oestrogen).<br><br>Take Notes: 46,XX + ambiguous genitalia → CAH (21-OHase deficiency) most common | Aromatase deficiency → placental androgens not converted → virilisation | Testicular feminisation → 46,XY phenotypic female | Foetal aromatase deficiency = 46,XX virilisation = enzyme diagnosis."},
/*177*/ {"q":"Down syndrome: patient with protruded abdomen and epicanthal folds and chromosomal abnormality, what is diagnosis?","o":["Trisomy down syndrome","Edward syndrome","Patau syndrome","Hematoma"],"a":0,"e":"Down syndrome (trisomy 21) presents with flat facies, epicanthal folds, protruding tongue, simian crease, and intellectual disability. It is the most common chromosomal abnormality compatible with survival.<br><br>Take Notes: Down syndrome → trisomy 21 | Features → flat facies + epicanthal folds + macroglossia + simian crease | Risk → increases with maternal age | Trisomy 21 = Down = most common viable chromosomal trisomy."},
/*178*/ {"q":"Loss of knee jerk due to damage:","o":["L2","L3","L4","L5"],"a":2,"e":"The knee jerk (patellar reflex) is mediated by L3-L4 nerve roots (predominantly L4). Loss indicates a lesion at L3-L4 level — anterior horn, nerve root, or femoral nerve.<br><br>Take Notes: knee jerk → L3-L4 (predominantly L4) | Ankle jerk → S1-S2 | Biceps reflex → C5-C6 | Triceps reflex → C7 | Loss of knee jerk = L4 nerve root or femoral nerve lesion."},
/*179*/ {"q":"45 year old diabetic lady since 10 years admitted in hospital due to shock like symptoms cause will develop pneumonia and developing shock like symptoms cause will she be given:","o":["Vasoconstriction","Increased vascular permeability","Increased peripheral resistance","Decrease hydrostatic pressure"],"a":1,"e":"Septic shock from pneumonia causes massive endothelial damage and increased vascular permeability, allowing protein-rich fluid to leak into the interstitium, causing tissue oedema and hypovolaemia despite normal or high cardiac output.<br><br>Take Notes: septic shock → endotoxin → endothelial damage → ↑vascular permeability → third spacing | Vasodilation (↓SVR) + ↑permeability = distributive shock hallmarks | Hypovolaemic → ↓permeability (vasoconstriction) | ↑Vascular permeability = septic shock mechanism."},
/*180*/ {"q":"A student observing a histology slide with thick vascular wall and pseudo stratified epithelium. Most likely structure is:","o":["3 layers of muscle, which structure?","Seminal vesicles","Epididymis","Vas deferens"],"a":3,"e":"The vas deferens has a thick muscular wall (3 layers of smooth muscle) lined by pseudostratified columnar epithelium with stereocilia. Its thick wall distinguishes it from the epididymis and produces the 'cord-like' feel on palpation of the spermatic cord.<br><br>Take Notes: vas deferens → thick 3-layer smooth muscle wall + pseudostratified epithelium with stereocilia | Epididymis → pseudostratified columnar with stereocilia (thinner wall) | Seminal vesicle → folded mucosal lining | 3-layer thick wall + pseudostratified = vas deferens."},
/*181*/ {"q":"Which of the following is true regarding increased N/C ratio:","o":["Abnormal DNA production","Increased RNA production","Abnormal RNA production","Increased N/C ratio"],"a":0,"e":"Increased nuclear-to-cytoplasmic (N/C) ratio is a hallmark of malignancy/dysplasia — the nucleus enlarges disproportionately due to abnormal DNA production and replication. Normal N/C ratio is low (small nucleus, abundant cytoplasm).<br><br>Take Notes: increased N/C ratio → malignancy/dysplasia | Enlarged nucleus → abnormal DNA production + replication | Combined with hyperchromasia + irregular nuclear membrane = classic malignancy histology | N/C ratio ↑ = abnormal DNA production = dysplasia marker."},
/*182*/ {"q":"A patient has complaint of headache due to high ICR. CSF is:","o":["ECF","Plasma","Interstitial fluid","Transcellular fluid"],"a":3,"e":"CSF is a specialised transcellular fluid — secreted by the choroid plexus (modified ependymal cells) into the ventricles. It is classified as transcellular because it occupies a body cavity separated by cell layers (not simply an ultrafiltrate of plasma).<br><br>Take Notes: CSF → transcellular fluid (secreted by choroid plexus) | Transcellular fluids → CSF + pleural + pericardial + synovial + bile | ECF → plasma + ISF (not CSF directly) | CSF = transcellular = choroid plexus secretion."},
/*183*/ {"q":"Premalignant condition of Skin Cancer is:","o":["Nitrosamide","Congenital Naevus","Lichen Planus","Xeroderma pigmentosum"],"a":3,"e":"Xeroderma pigmentosum is a rare autosomal recessive disorder of DNA repair (defective nucleotide excision repair), causing extreme UV sensitivity, multiple premalignant lesions, and a high risk of skin cancers (SCC, BCC, melanoma).<br><br>Take Notes: xeroderma pigmentosum → defective NER (nucleotide excision repair) → UV damage accumulates | High risk → SCC + BCC + melanoma | Lichen planus → ~1-3% SCC risk (lower) | Xeroderma pigmentosum = the extreme UV-sensitive premalignant condition."},
/*184*/ {"q":"Patient having Stiff Neck Fever Slight SOR. CSF: Increase protein glucose 40 and WBC increased. Which of the following is routinely done for the test of meningitis?","o":["Lumbar puncture","Blood Culture","CSF Culture","Glucose"],"a":0,"e":"Lumbar puncture (CSF examination) is the definitive test for meningitis — it shows elevated WBC, elevated protein, low glucose (bacterial), and identifies the causative organism on culture and sensitivity.<br><br>Take Notes: meningitis diagnosis → lumbar puncture (CSF analysis) | CT first → if raised ICP suspected (papilloedema/focal deficits) | CSF bacterial meningitis → ↑WBC (neutrophils) + ↓glucose + ↑protein | LP = the definitive meningitis test."},
/*185*/ {"q":"Police man sent to you he has some opioid and other drugs found in urine. Because his urine has some other drug found. What will be his response?","o":["Infectious mononucleosis involve Atypical Lymphocytes","Denial","Blaming the doctors","Politely acceptance"],"a":1,"e":"When confronted with objective evidence of drug use (urine drug screen), denial is the most common initial psychological defence mechanism in addiction. Acceptance comes later in the stages of change (Prochaska model).<br><br>Take Notes: denial → most common initial response to confronting evidence of substance use | Stages of change → precontemplation → contemplation → preparation → action → maintenance | Acceptance → required for treatment engagement | Denial = most common = the initial addiction defence mechanism."},
/*186*/ {"q":"Infectious mononucleosis involve which type of cells appear as atypical lymphocytes:","o":["Atypical Lymphocytes — Infected B cells","Activated B cells","NK cells","Plasma cells"],"a":0,"e":"In EBV mononucleosis, the atypical lymphocytes on blood smear are activated CD8+ T cells (reactive T lymphocytes responding to EBV-infected B cells) — NOT the infected B cells themselves. They appear large with abundant cytoplasm and irregular nuclei.<br><br>Take Notes: mononucleosis atypical lymphocytes → reactive CD8+ T cells (not infected B cells) | EBV → infects B cells (CD21 receptor) | Atypical lymphocytes = reactive T cells = the smear finding | EBV + B cell infection → T cell reaction → atypical lymphocytes."},
/*187*/ {"q":"IM shows Atypical Lymphocytes activated T cells but Infected Cells are B cells but Activated T cells which include Activated T cells:","o":["NK cells","Plasma cells","Activated T cells","Macrophages"],"a":2,"e":"Activated CD8+ T cells (cytotoxic T lymphocytes) are the atypical lymphocytes seen on peripheral blood smear in EBV mononucleosis. They are reacting against EBV-infected B cells.<br><br>Take Notes: EBV → infects B cells → CD8+ T cells activate → atypical lymphocytes on smear | CD8+ CTLs = the smear cells (not B cells) | Downey cells = the large atypical lymphocytes | Activated T cells = reactive CD8+ CTLs = EBV mononucleosis smear finding."},
/*188*/ {"q":"A patient Detached embolus from deep vein of leg will lodge in:","o":["Heart","Lung","Inferior vena cava","Superior vena cava"],"a":1,"e":"A DVT embolus from the leg veins travels via the inferior vena cava → right atrium → right ventricle → pulmonary artery → lodges in the lung (pulmonary embolism). The lung is the first capillary bed encountered.<br><br>Take Notes: DVT embolus pathway → deep leg vein → IVC → right heart → pulmonary artery → lung | Paradoxical embolism → through PFO → systemic circulation | PE → dyspnoea + pleuritic chest pain + haemoptysis | Lung = first capillary bed = DVT embolus destination."},
/*189*/ {"q":"Emboli first go to IVC then Right. Stab wound at left 5th ICS just lateral to sternum. Structure damage:","o":["Left lung","Left pleura","Pericardium","Left hilum of kidney"],"a":2,"e":"A stab wound at the left 5th intercostal space just lateral to the sternum penetrates the pericardium and may reach the left ventricle/cardiac apex. The heart lies behind the 3rd-6th ribs and the pericardium is 3-4 cm deep at this location.<br><br>Take Notes: left 5th ICS parasternal stab → pericardium + left ventricle at risk | Cardiac tamponade → Beck's triad (hypotension + muffled sounds + raised JVP) | Left pleura → more lateral | Pericardium = left 5th ICS lateral sternum = the structure damaged."},
/*190*/ {"q":"A 6 year old child with apathy, peripheral oedema. Blood smear: microscope shows polychromasia. Diagnostic investigation will be:","o":["Approach to pericardiocentesis","2nd ics","5th Left intercostal space","5th ics Left intercostal space mid axillary line"],"a":2,"e":"Polychromasia on blood smear indicates active haemolysis with reticulocytosis. The diagnostic investigation (and pericardiocentesis approach) is via the 5th left intercostal space, but in context this question asks about the haemolytic anaemia in the child — direct Coombs test confirms immune-mediated haemolysis.<br><br>Take Notes: polychromasia → reticulocytosis → haemolytic anaemia | Subxiphoid or 5th ICS left → pericardiocentesis route | Direct Coombs → immune haemolytic anaemia | 5th left ICS = pericardiocentesis = the cardiac access point."},
/*191*/ {"q":"The maturation of T cells occur between 5th and 6th intercostal:","o":["Bone Marrow","Thymus","Trachaes","Payers patches"],"a":1,"e":"T cells mature and undergo selection in the thymus (derived from 3rd pharyngeal pouch). They differentiate into CD4+ helper and CD8+ cytotoxic T cells through positive and negative selection in the thymic cortex and medulla.<br><br>Take Notes: T cell maturation → thymus | B cell maturation → bone marrow | Positive selection → thymic cortex (MHC recognition) | Negative selection → thymic medulla (self-tolerance) | Thymus = T cell education = the site of T cell maturation."},
/*192*/ {"q":"B cell by Bone marrow. Infected Cells are B cell by Bone marrow. T cell by Thymus. Oesophagus. Blood supply of Lower third of Oesophagus:","o":["Descending thoracic aorta","Inferior thyroid artery","Left gastric","Inferior vena cava"],"a":2,"e":"The lower third of the oesophagus is supplied by the left gastric artery (branch of coeliac axis) and the left inferior phrenic artery. The oesophageal varices of portal hypertension occur at this level through the left gastric vein connections.<br><br>Take Notes: lower 1/3 oesophagus → left gastric artery (coeliac) | Middle 1/3 → thoracic aorta branches | Upper 1/3 → inferior thyroid artery | Left gastric = lower oesophagus = portal-systemic connection site."},
/*193*/ {"q":"Hepatoma causes compression of which of the following:","o":["Portal vein","Left gastric","Hepatic duct","Left gastric vein"],"a":0,"e":"Hepatocellular carcinoma (hepatoma) commonly causes portal vein thrombosis/compression — tumour invades the portal vein, causing portal hypertension and its sequelae (varices, ascites, splenomegaly).<br><br>Take Notes: hepatoma → portal vein invasion/compression (most characteristic) | Portal vein thrombosis → portal hypertension | Alpha-fetoprotein → hepatoma marker | Portal vein = hepatoma compression = the vascular complication."},
/*194*/ {"q":"In Portal vein blockage there will be compress early and dilated:","o":["In IVC blockage compress there will be early","Hepatoma will compress","Portal vein","Hepatic duct"],"a":2,"e":"Portal vein obstruction causes pre-hepatic portal hypertension — dilated portal vein with collateral formation, splenomegaly, and oesophageal varices. The portal vein itself dilates proximal to the obstruction.<br><br>Take Notes: portal vein blockage → pre-hepatic portal hypertension | Dilated → portal vein + collaterals | Splenomegaly → from congestion | Portal vein = the vessel that dilates in pre-hepatic obstruction."},
/*195*/ {"q":"Loss of Cytoplasmic mRNA in Apoptotic cell is:","o":["Loss of Lysosomes","Loss of Mitochondria","Loss of Cytoplasmic mRNA","Eosinophilia in Apoptosis"],"a":2,"e":"Apoptosis involves controlled fragmentation of cellular components: cytoplasmic mRNA is degraded by endonucleases and RNases as part of the programmed dismantling. This prevents potential oncogenic RNA from being released.<br><br>Take Notes: apoptosis → loss of cytoplasmic mRNA (endonuclease/RNase degradation) | Also → membrane blebbing + nuclear condensation + apoptotic body formation | No inflammation (unlike necrosis) | Loss of mRNA = apoptosis = controlled cellular dismantling."},
/*196*/ {"q":"The fibres transmitting pain and temperature are:","o":["A Alpha fibres","A Beta fibres","C fibres","A Delta fibres"],"a":2,"e":"C fibres (unmyelinated, slow conduction, <2 m/s) carry slow, burning, diffuse pain and crude temperature. A-delta fibres (thinly myelinated, 5-30 m/s) carry fast, sharp, well-localised pain and cold. Both carry nociceptive information.<br><br>Take Notes: C fibres → slow pain (burning) + temperature (unmyelinated) | A-delta → fast pain (sharp) + cold (thinly myelinated) | A-alpha → proprioception + motor | A-beta → touch/pressure | C fibres = the primary pain + temperature fibre."},
/*197*/ {"q":"Post mortem thrombosis seen in:","o":["Chicken fat Appearance","Post Mortem Thrombus","Ante mortem","Arterial coagulation"],"a":0,"e":"Post-mortem thrombi (agonal clots) show a 'chicken fat and red-currant jelly' layered appearance — pale yellow (chicken fat) layer from settled leucocytes/platelets overlying a red (red-currant jelly) layer from settled RBCs. This distinguishes them from ante-mortem thrombi (lines of Zahn).<br><br>Take Notes: post-mortem thrombus → chicken fat + red-currant jelly appearance (RBC layering) | Ante-mortem thrombus → lines of Zahn (alternating fibrin + platelets + RBCs) | Chicken fat = post-mortem = the layered appearance clue."},
/*198*/ {"q":"Following mechanism of renal stones by which renal stones causes:","o":["Hypertrophy of renal mucosa","Atrophy of renal mucosa","Dysplasia of renal mucosa","Hyperplasia of renal mucosa"],"a":3,"e":"Chronic renal calculi cause mucosal irritation and hyperplasia of the transitional epithelium (urothelium) lining the renal pelvis/ureter. Long-standing irritation from stones is a risk factor for squamous cell carcinoma of the renal pelvis.<br><br>Take Notes: chronic renal stones → mucosal hyperplasia (urothelial) | Long-standing irritation → SCC of renal pelvis risk | Obstructive nephropathy → hydronephrosis | Hyperplasia = mucosal response = chronic stone irritation."},
/*199*/ {"q":"A few days old newborn with abdominal distension and vomiting. Hirschsprung disease. Which of following ganglia is absent?","o":["Parasympathetic ganglia receive innervation from which segment of cord?","S2,3,4","L2-4","S5,S1"],"a":1,"e":"Hirschsprung disease results from absence of Auerbach's (myenteric) plexus ganglion cells in the distal colon — due to failure of neural crest cell migration. The parasympathetic innervation of the pelvic viscera originates from S2-S4 (pelvic splanchnic nerves).<br><br>Take Notes: Hirschsprung → absent myenteric ganglia (neural crest migration failure) | Parasympathetic pelvic innervation → S2-S4 (pelvic splanchnic nerves) | Aganglionic segment → functional obstruction | S2-S4 = parasympathetic pelvic supply = the relevant cord segment."},
/*200*/ {"q":"Husband and Wife came to you regarding their concern that they both are thalassemia carriers and they are worried about their baby. Prenatal monitoring is necessary in this case because:","o":["They are thalassemia carriers","Prenatal monitoring is necessary for their baby","They Both are thalassemia carriers and clinicomorphological picture","No risk of Transmission"],"a":2,"e":"When both parents are thalassaemia trait carriers (heterozygous), each pregnancy has a 25% chance of major thalassaemia (homozygous), 50% carrier, 25% normal. Prenatal diagnosis by CVS or amniocentesis identifies affected foetuses.<br><br>Take Notes: two carrier parents → 25% major thalassaemia + 50% carrier + 25% normal (Mendelian ratio) | Prenatal diagnosis → CVS (10-13 weeks) or amniocentesis (15-20 weeks) | Both carriers = the indication for prenatal monitoring | 25% risk major = the reason for prenatal surveillance."}
];
